00fran }}\n* {{Citation |last=Franklin |first=Stan |year=2003 |contribution=IDA: A Conscious Artefact |title=Machine Consciousness |editor-first=Owen |editor-last=Holland |place=Exeter, UK |publisher=Imprint Academic}}\n* {{Citation |last=Freeman |first=Walter |year=1999 |title=How Brains make up their Minds |publisher=Phoenix |place=London, UK |isbn=978-0-231-12008-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Gamez |first=David |year=2008 |title=Progress in machine consciousness |journal=Consciousness and Cognition |volume=17 |issue=3 |doi=10.1016/j.concog.2007.04.005 |pmid=17572107 |pages=887\u2013910}}\n* {{Citation |last=Haikonen |first=Pentti |year=2003 |title=The Cognitive Approach to Conscious Machines |publisher=Imprint Academic |place=Exeter, UK |isbn=978-0-907845-42-3 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/cognitiveapproac0000haik }}\n* {{Citation |last=Haikonen |first=Pentti |year=2012 |title=Consciousness and Robot Sentience |publisher=World Scientific |place=Singapore |isbn=978-981-4407-15-1}}\n* {{Citation |last=Haikonen |first=Pentti |year=2019 |title=Consciousness and Robot Sentience: 2nd Edition |publisher=World Scientific |place=Singapore |isbn=978-981-120-504-0}}\n* {{Citation |last=Koch |first=Christof |year=2004 |title=The Quest for Consciousness: A Neurobiological Approach |publisher=Roberts & Company Publishers |place=Pasadena, CA |isbn=978-0-9747077-0-9}}\n* {{Citation |last=Lewis |first=David |year=1972 |title=Psychophysical and theoretical identifications |journal=Australasian Journal of Philosophy |volume=50 |issue=3 |pages=249\u2013258 |doi=10.1080/00048407212341301}}\n* {{Citation |last=Putnam |first=Hilary |year=1967 |title=The nature of mental states in Capitan and Merrill (eds.) Art, Mind and Religion |publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press}}\n* {{Citation |last=Reggia |first=James |year=2013 |title=The rise of machine consciousness: Studying consciousness with computational models |journal=Neural Networks |volume=44 |doi=10.1016/j.neunet.2013.03.011 |pmid=23597599 |pages=112\u2013131}}\n* {{Citation |last=Sanz |first= Ricardo |last2=L\u00f3pez |first2=I |last3=Rodr\u00edguez |first3=M |last4=Hern\u00e1ndez |first4=C |year=2007 |title=Principles for consciousness in integrated cognitive control |journal= Neural Networks |volume=20 |doi=10.1016/j.neunet.2007.09.012 |pages=938\u2013946 |pmid=17936581 |issue=9|url=http://cogprints.org/5941/1/ASLAB%2DA%2D2007%2D011.pdf }}\n* {{Citation |last=Searle |first=John |year=2004 |title=Mind: A Brief Introduction |publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n* {{Citation |last=Shanahan |first=Murray |year=2006 |title=A cognitive architecture that combines internal simulation with a global workspace |journal=Consciousness and Cognition |volume=15 |issue=2 |doi=10.1016/j.concog.2005.11.005 |pmid=16384715 |pages=443\u2013449}}\n* {{Citation |last=Sun |first=Ron  |title=Accounting for the computational basis of consciousness: A connectionist approach |journal=Consciousness and Cognition |volume=8 |date=December 1999 |doi= 10.1006/ccog.1999.0405 |pages=529\u2013565 |pmid=10600249 |issue=4|citeseerx=10.1.1.42.2681  }}\n* {{Citation |last=Sun |first=Ron |year=2001 |title=Computation, reduction, and teleology of consciousness |journal=Cognitive Systems Research |volume=1 |pages=241\u2013249 |doi=10.1016/S1389-0417(00)00013-9 |issue= 4|citeseerx=10.1.1.20.8764 }}\n* {{Citation |last=Takeno |first=Junichi |last2=Inaba |first2=K |last3=Suzuki |first3=T  |title=Experiments and examination of '''mirror image cognition''' using a small robot |journal=The 6th IEEE International Symposium on Computational Intelligence in Robotics and Automation |pages=493\u2013498 |publisher=CIRA 2005 |date=June 27\u201330, 2005 |doi=10.1109/CIRA.2005.1554325 |place=Espoo Finland |isbn=978-0-7803-9355-4}}\n* {{Citation |last=Cleeremans |first=Axel |year=2001 |title=Implicit learning and consciousness |url=http://srsc.ulb.ac.be/axcWWW/papers/pdf/01-AXCLJ.pdf}}\n* {{Citation|last=Chalmers |first=David |year=2011 |title=A Computational Foundation for the Study of Cognition |journal=Journal of Cognitive Science |pages=323\u2013357 |url=http://j-cs.org/gnuboard/bbs/download.php?bo_table=__vol012i4&wr_id=1&no=0 |place=Seoul Republic of Korea |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151223105456/http://j-cs.org/gnuboard/bbs/download.php?bo_table=__vol012i4&wr_id=1&no=0 |archivedate=2015-12-23 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Baars | first1 = Bernard | last2 = Franklin | first2 = Stan | year = 2003 | title = How conscious experience and working memory interact | url = http://cogprints.org/5854/1/TICSarticle2003.pdf| journal = Trends in Cognitive Sciences | volume = 7 | issue = 4| pages = 166\u2013172 | doi=10.1016/s1364-6613(03)00056-1| pmid = 12691765 }}\n* Casti, John L. \"The Cambridge Quintet: A Work of Scientific Speculation\", Perseus Books Group, 1998\n* Franklin, S, B J Baars, U Ramamurthy, and Matthew Ventura. 2005. [http://www.brains-minds-media.org/archive/150 The role of consciousness in memory]. Brains, Minds and Media 1: 1\u201338, pdf.\n* Haikonen, Pentti (2004), ''Conscious Machines and Machine Emotions'', presented at Workshop on Models for Machine Consciousness, Antwerp, BE, June 2004.\n* McCarthy, John (1971\u20131987), [http://www-formal.stanford.edu/jmc/generality/generality.html ''Generality in Artificial Intelligence''].  Stanford University, 1971-1987.\n* Penrose, Roger, [[The Emperor's New Mind]], 1989.\n* Sternberg, Eliezer J. (2007) ''Are You a Machine?: The Brain, the Mind, And What It Means to be Human.'' Amherst, NY: Prometheus Books.\n* Suzuki T., Inaba K., Takeno, Junichi (2005),'' Conscious Robot That '''Distinguishes Between Self and Others''' and Implements Imitation Behavior'', ('''Best Paper of IEA/AIE2005'''), Innovations in Applied Artificial Intelligence, 18th International Conference on Industrial and Engineering Applications of Artificial Intelligence and Expert Systems, pp.&nbsp;101\u2013110, IEA/AIE 2005, Bari, Italy, June 22\u201324, 2005.\n* Takeno, Junichi (2006), [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927130938/http://www.d6.dion.ne.jp/~takenof/SAR-LAL-Takeno.pdf ''The '''Self-Aware Robot''' -A Response to Reactions to Discovery News-''], HRI Press, August 2006.\n* Zagal, J.C., Lipson, H. (2009) \"[http://ccsl.mae.cornell.edu/sites/default/files/GECCO09_Zagal.pdf Self-Reflection in Evolutionary Robotics]\",  Proceedings of the Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference, pp 2179\u20132188, GECCO 2009.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.slideserve.com/astro/artefactual-consciousness-depiction-and-an-example-in-robot-usable-models-of-visual-consciousness-igor-aleksander-intelligent-and-interactive-systems-group Artefactual consciousness depiction by Professor Igor Aleksander]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110719195048/http://www.aco.gatech.edu/conference/focs-aco/abstracts.html FOCS 2009: Manuel Blum - Can (Theoretical Computer) Science come to grips with Consciousness?]\n* [http://www.Conscious-Robots.com www.Conscious-Robots.com], Machine Consciousness and Conscious Robots Portal.\n\n{{Consciousness}}\n\n[[Category:Artificial intelligence]]\n[[Category:Consciousness]]\n[[Category:Consciousness studies]]\n[[Category:Computational neuroscience]]\n", "name_user": "Scienceteacher3k", "label": "safe", "comment": "restored alphabetical order", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_consciousness"}
{"title_page": "Rick James", "text_new": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, dancer, bandleader and record producer}}\n{{other uses|Rick James (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rick James\n| image              = Rick James in Lifestyles of the Rich 1984.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = James on ''[[Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous]]'' in 1984\n| birth_name         = James Ambrose Johnson Jr.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1948|2|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| alias              = Ricky Matthews\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2004|8|6|1948|2|1}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Singing|Singer]]|[[Songwriter]]|[[Arrangement|Arranger]]|[[Record producer]]|[[Dance|Dancer]]}}\n| years_active       = 1964\u20132004\n| children           = 3\n| relatives          = \n| website            = {{URL|www.rickjames.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]|[[Soul music|soul]]|[[funk]]|[[funk rock]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Holden |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/09/06/arts/punk-rock-rick-james.html |title=Punk Rock - Rick James |work=The New York Times |date=September 6, 1981 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jim |last=Sullivan |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-10-13/entertainment/9104020472_1_hard-core-punk-rock-heavy-metal |title=The Age of Hyphen-Rock |website=Chicago Tribune |date=October 13, 1991 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>|[[rock music|rock]]|[[doo-wop]]|[[dance-punk]]}}\n| instrument = Vocals, bass, guitar, keyboards, drums, other percussion instruments\n| label = {{hlist|[[Gordy Records|Gordy]]|[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]|[[A&M Records|A&M]]|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Mynah Birds]]|Stone City Band|Heaven and Earth|[[Mary Jane Girls]]|Process and the Doo Rags|[[Val Young]]|[[Eddie Murphy]]|[[Teena Marie]]}}\n  }}<!--end-module-->\n}}\n\n'''James Ambrose Johnson Jr.''' (February 1, 1948 \u2013 August 6, 2004), better known by his stage name '''Rick James''', was an American [[singer-songwriter]], [[multi-instrumentalist]] and [[Record producer|producer]]. Born and raised in [[Buffalo, New York]], James began his musical career in his teen years. He was in various bands before entering the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] and to avoid [[conscription|being drafted]] in 1964, James [[desertion|deserted]] to [[Toronto]], Canada, where he formed the rock band [[the Mynah Birds]], who eventually signed a recording deal with [[Motown|Motown Records]] in 1966. James' career with the group halted after military authorities discovered his whereabouts and eventually convicted James to a one-year prison term related to the draft charges. After being released, James moved to California where he started a variety of rock and funk groups in the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\nAfter forming the locally popular Stone City Band in his hometown of Buffalo in 1977, James finally found success as a recording artist after signing with Motown's [[Gordy Records]], releasing the album ''[[Come Get It!]]'' in 1978 which produced the hits \"[[You and I (Rick James song)|You & I]]\" and \"[[Mary Jane (Rick James song)|Mary Jane]].\" In 1981, James released his most successful album, ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'', which included career-defining hits such as \"[[Give It to Me Baby]]\" and \"[[Super Freak]],\" the latter song becoming his biggest [[Crossover music|crossover single]], mixing elements of funk, disco, rock and [[new wave music|new wave]]. James was also known for his [[soul music|soulful]] ballads such as \"Fire & Desire\" and \"[[Ebony Eyes (Rick James song)|Ebony Eyes]].\" In addition, James also had a successful career as a songwriter and producer for other artists including [[Teena Marie]], the [[Mary Jane Girls]], [[the Temptations]], [[Eddie Murphy]] and [[Smokey Robinson]].\n\nJames' mainstream success had peaked with the release of his album ''[[Glow (Rick James album)|Glow]]'' in 1985 and his appearance on the popular TV show, ''[[The A-Team]]''. His subsequent album releases failed to sell as well as their predecessors. Rapper [[MC Hammer]] sampled James' \"Super Freak\" for his 1990 hit, \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\" which won [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]] at the [[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|1991 Grammy Awards]]. James received his only Grammy for composing the song.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/rick-james|title=Rick James|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> By the early 1990s, James' career was hampered by his drug addiction and he was embroiled with legal issues. In 1993, James was convicted for two separate instances of kidnapping and torturing two different women while under the influence of [[crack cocaine]], resulting in a three-year sentence at [[Folsom State Prison]]. James was released on parole in 1996 and released the album ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'' in 1997. James's health problems halted his career again after he had a mild stroke during a concert in 1998, and he announced a semi-retirement.\n\nIn 2004, James's career returned to mainstream [[Popular culture|pop culture]] after he appeared in an episode of ''[[Chappelle's Show]]''. The segment involved a [[Charlie Murphy]] ''[[E! True Hollywood Story|True Hollywood Stories]]''-style skit that satirized James' wild lifestyle in the 1980s. This resulted in renewed interest in his music and that year he returned to perform on the road. James died later that year from [[heart failure]] at age 56.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Early life ===\nJohnson was born on February 1, 1948, in [[Buffalo, New York]], to Mabel (n\u00e9e Sims) and James Ambrose Johnson Sr. He was one of eight children. James's father, an autoworker, left the family when James was 10. His mother was a dancer for [[Katherine Dunham]], and later worked as a [[Numbers game|numbers-runner]] to earn a living.<ref name=\"glowreview\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/05/rick-james-reveled-in-super-freaky-autobiography-i-was-caligula/ |title=Rick James' insane life of sex, drugs and music |last=Getlen |first=Larry |date=July 5, 2014 |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> James's mother would take him on her collecting route, and it was in bars where she worked that James saw performers such as [[John Coltrane]], [[Miles Davis]], and [[Etta James]] perform.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James claimed later, in the autobiography ''Glow'', that he lost his virginity at \"age 9 or 10\" to a 14-year-old local girl, claiming his \"kinky nature came in early.\"<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James eventually attended [[Orchard Park High School]] and [[Bennett High School (Buffalo, New York)|Bennett High School]] prior to dropping out. James was introduced to drugs at an early age and was busted for burglary as a young teen.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> Due to his stints in jail for theft, James entered the [[United States Navy]] at 14 or 15, lying about his age, to avoid the [[Conscription in the United States#Vietnam|draft]]. During that time, he also became a drummer for local jazz groups in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> Due to him missing his twice-monthly [[United States Navy Reserve|Reserve]] sessions aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}, he found himself ordered to Vietnam.<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\n=== Early career ===\nIn 1964, James fled to [[Toronto]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book |title=Glow: The autobiography of Rick James|last=James|first=Rick|publisher=Atria Books|last2=Ritz |first2=David|lastauthoramp=y|year=2014|isbn=9781476764146|edition=First hardcover|location=New York|pages=|oclc=862348461}}</ref> Soon after his arrival three drunk white men tried to jump him outside a club; a trio of other guys came to his aid. One of the men who came to his aid was [[Levon Helm]], who at the time was an undiscovered member of [[Ronnie Hawkins]]' backing band.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/07/rick-james-memoir-moments-glow.html|title=The 12 Most Rick James\u2013y Moments in Rick James's New Memoir, Glow|last=Carley|first=Brennan|date=July 11, 2014|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> He invited James to their show later that night and he ended up performing onstage with them.<ref name=\":0\" />  In Toronto James made friends with local musicians [[Neil Young]] and [[Joni Mitchell]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> To avoid being caught by military authorities, James went under the assumed name, \"Ricky James Matthews\".<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> That same year, James formed [[the Mynah Birds]], a band that produced a fusion of [[Soul music|soul]], [[Folk music|folk]] and [[rock music]]. In 1965, the band briefly recorded for the Canadian division of [[Columbia Records]], releasing the single, \"Mynah Bird Hop\"/\"Mynah Bird Song\". At one point, [[Nick St. Nicholas]] of later [[Steppenwolf (band)|Steppenwolf]] fame was a member; eventually bassist [[Bruce Palmer]] replaced him by the time \"Mynah Bird Hop\" was recorded. James and Palmer recruited guitarists Tom Morgan and Xavier Taylor and drummer Rick Mason to form a new Mynah Birds lineup, and soon traveled to [[Detroit]] to record with [[Motown]]. Before the group began recording their first songs for the label, Morgan left, unhappy about the label's attitude towards the musicians. Neil Young eventually took his place. It was while in Detroit that James met his musical heroes, [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Stevie Wonder]]. After meeting Wonder and telling him his name, Wonder felt the name \"Ricky James Matthews\" was \"too long\", and instead told James to shorten it to \"Ricky James\".<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\nIn 1966, a financial dispute in Toronto between James and the Mynah Birds' handler, Morley Shelman<ref name=\"Benjaminson, p. 42\">Benjaminson, p. 42</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org/2012/04/mynah-birds-in-depth-exclusive.html|title=Neil Young News: The Mynah Birds: An In Depth Exclusive|website=neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\">Durchholz, p. 23</ref> led to Motown's learning of James's fugitive status with the Navy. Hoping to preempt any scrutiny, Motown execs told Rick they would not be releasing any more of his material and \"convinced\" him to come back and work with them after straightening out his legal issues.<ref name=\"Benjaminson, p. 42\"/><ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\"/> James surrendered himself to the [[FBI]], and, in May 1966, was sentenced by the Navy to five months' hard labor for \"Unauthorized Absence\". He was not yet 19 years old. James escaped from the Brooklyn Naval Brig after only six weeks' confinement, but following another six months [[Fugitive|on the lam]], surrendered himself a second time. With help from his mother, James found legal assistance from his cousin, future Congressman [[Louis Stokes]] and an attorney, former Marine Captain John Bracken, who pled James' second [[court-martial]] down from a potential five years' hard labor to five months.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /><ref>Benjaminson, pp. 43-47</ref> After his release from [[Portsmouth Naval Prison]] in August 1967, James returned to Toronto<ref>Benjaminson, pp. 47-48</ref> and endured another detention, initially derailing resumption of his career with Mynah Bird bandmate [[Neil Merryweather]], with whom he would later collaborate, first at Motown and then in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\"/><ref>Bejaminson pp. 50, 53</ref>\n\nIn 1968, again working under the pseudonym Ricky Matthews, James produced and wrote songs at Motown for acts such as [[The Miracles]], [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]], and [[The Spinners (American R&B group)|The Spinners]]. According to James, he briefly got involved in [[procuring (prostitution)|pimp activity]] during this time, but stopped because he felt he was not qualified for it due to the harsh activity and the abuse of women there.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> It was during this third stint at Motown that James met musician [[Greg Reeves]]. Reeves, hoping to find a better situation than the [[United States dollar|US$]]38 a week (US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|85|1968}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) he was earning as a session bassist for [[Berry Gordy]], joined James, looking to \"hitch a lift from Neil Young's rising star,\" and relocated to Los Angeles.<ref>Bejaminson pp. 56</ref> \n\nOn one of his first night in Los Angeles, James was crashing on musician [[Stephen Stills]]' couch. When he awoke he saw a stoned young man sitting on the floor in the [[lotus position]]. The man's wrists were bleeding so a scared James sought help. James was later formally introduced to the man who was [[Jim Morrison]], lead singer of [[the Doors]]. After the Doors opened for [[Buffalo Springfield]] at the [[Whisky a Go Go]], Morrison tricked James into taking [[Acid (drug)|acid]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn California, James initially worked as a duo with Greg Reeves, but soon after James introduced Reeves to Neil Young, it was Reeves, not James, who was hired as bassist for the newly formed rock [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]], [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /><ref name=\"nickwarburton.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nickwarburton.com/wordpress/?cat=7|title=Rick James's Early Years|website=nickwarburton.com |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Around this time James formed several versions of the rock band Salt'N'Pepper<ref name=\"nickwarburton.com\" /> and got involved with [[Hairdresser|hair stylist]] [[Jay Sebring]], who agreed to invest in his music.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> In 1969, James claimed that Sebring invited him to attend a party at actress [[Sharon Tate]]\u2019s house, but he was too [[Hangover|hungover]] to get out of bed. The next morning he discovered that Sebring had been [[Tate murders|murdered]] when he saw the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' headline \"Sharon Tate, Four Others Murdered.\"<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1970, James and Salt'N'Pepper member Ed Roth later were included in Bruce Palmer's solo album ''[[The Cycle Is Complete|The Cycle is Complete]]''. The duo also recorded as part of the group Heaven and Earth in Toronto. Heaven and Earth eventually changed their name to Great White Cane and recorded a self-titled album for the Los Angeles label Lion Records, released in 1972. James formed another band, Hot Lips, afterwards.\n\n=== Solo career ===\nIn 1973, James signed with [[A&M Records]], where his first single under the name Rick James, \"My Mama\", was released in 1974, becoming a club hit in Europe.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> \n\nIn 1976, James returned to Buffalo, New York, and formed the Stone City Band and recorded the song \"Get Up and Dance!\", which was his second single to be released. In 1977, James and the Stone City Band signed a contract with Motown's Gordy Records imprint, where they began recording their first album in New York City.\n\nIn April 1978, James released his debut solo album, ''[[Come Get It!]]'', which included the Stone City Band. The album launched the top 20 hit, \"[[You and I (Rick James song)|You and I]]\", which became his first number-one R&B hit. The album also included the hit single, \"[[Mary Jane (Rick James song)|Mary Jane]]\". It eventually sold two million copies, launching James's musical career to stardom, and helping out Motown Records at a time when label fortunes had dwindled.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Bob|url=https://archive.org/details/michaeljacksonma00jone|url-access=registration|quote=sold over 1 million copies. Street Songs.|title=Michael Jackson, the Man Behind the Mask: An Insider's Story of the King of Pop|last2=Brown|first2=Stacy|date=2005|publisher=Select Books Inc.|isbn=978-1-59079-072-4|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/michaeljacksonma00jone/page/42 42]|language=en}}</ref> In early 1979, James's second album, ''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]'', followed the previous album's success, eventually selling a million copies. A third album, ''[[Fire It Up (Rick James album)|Fire It Up]]'', was released in late 1979 going [[Recording Industry Association of America certification|gold]]. Around that same period, James launched his first headlining tour, the Fire It Up Tour, and agreed to invite the then-upcoming artist, [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], as well as singer [[Teena Marie]], as his opening act.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James had produced Marie's successful Motown debut album, ''[[Wild and Peaceful (Teena Marie album)|Wild and Peaceful]]'' and was featured on the hit duet, \"I'm a Sucker (For Your Love)\". James was credited with naming Marie, \"Lady Tee\", on the song, a nickname that stuck with Marie for the rest of her career. The Fire It Up tour led to James developing a bitter rivalry with Prince, after he accused the musician of ripping off his act.<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\n{{listen\n| Type           = single\n| filename       = Rick James - Super Freak excerpt.ogg\n| format         = [[Ogg]]\n| title          = \"Super Freak\"}}\n\nFollowing the end of the tour in 1980, James released the ballads-heavy ''[[Garden of Love (album)|Garden of Love]]'', which became his fourth gold record. In 1981, James recorded his best-selling album to date, ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'', which like his previous four albums, was a [[concept album]]. ''Street Songs'' featured a fusion mix of different genres, including rock and [[new wave music|new wave]], as well as James's brand of crossover funk, enabling James's own style of \"punk funk\". The album featured hit singles such as \"[[Ghetto Life (song)|Ghetto Life]]\", the Teena Marie duet \"Fire and Desire\", \"[[Give It to Me Baby]]\", and his biggest crossover hit to date, \"[[Super Freak]]\", which peaked at number 16 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and sold over 1 million copies. ''Street Songs'' peaked at number one R&B and number three pop, and sold over 3 million copies alone in the United States.<ref name=\":4\" /> Following up that success, James released two more gold albums, 1982's ''[[Throwin' Down]]'' and 1983's ''[[Cold Blooded (Rick James album)|Cold Blooded]]''.\n\nDuring this period, envious of Prince's success as producer of other acts including [[The Time (band)|The Time]] and [[Vanity 6]], James launched the acts Process and the Doo-Rags, and the [[Mary Jane Girls]], featuring his former background singer Joanne \"JoJo\" McDuffie as the lead vocalist and background performer, finding success with the latter group, due to the hits, \"[[All Night Long (Mary Jane Girls song)|All Night Long]]\", \"Candy Man\", and \"[[In My House]]\". In 1982, James produced the Temptations' Top 10 R&B hit, \"[[Standing On The Top (song)|Standing On The Top]]\". In 1983, James recorded the hit duet, \"Ebony Eyes\", with singer [[Smokey Robinson]], as well as a ballad \"Tell Me What You Want\" with an introduction by Billy Dee Williams. In 1985, James produced another hit for entertainer [[Eddie Murphy]] with the song \"[[Party All the Time]]\". That same year he appeared on an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]'' with [[Isaac Hayes]]. After the release of his ninth solo album, ''[[The Flag (album)|The Flag]]'', in 1986, James signed with [[Warner Bros. Records]], which released the album ''[[Wonderful (Rick James album)|Wonderful]]'' in 1988, featuring the hit, \"Loosey's Rap\".\n\nJames's controversial and provocative image became troublesome sometimes. Famous for promoting the use of [[marijuana]] live in concerts during a time that simple possession could lead to a long term prison sentence, James was often threatened by cops in various cities that he would be arrested if he smoked marijuana on stage during performances of songs such as \"Fire It Up\" and \"Mary Jane\". According to Kerry Gordy, most Motown executives erroneously thought the latter song was a \"simple cute love song to a girl\" not knowing the song was about marijuana.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nJames' overtly sexual bravado made it tough for him to be a bigger mainstream act. After the debut of the fledgling music video network [[MTV]] in August of 1981, James tried to present the music video to \"Super Freak\" to the label, only for the channel to turn the video down. James accused the network of racism.{{sfn|Denisof|1988|pp=69\u201371}} MTV denied this, stating the real reason \"Super Freak\" was turned down by MTV was because they felt James' video was too vulgar for the channel. When younger artists such as Prince and [[Michael Jackson]] found fame on the channel, James accused the two singers of being \"tokens\" in a 1983 interview, demanding that any black artist that has a video aired on MTV take their video off the channel in protest. James' rant was cosigned by [[David Bowie]], who argued with an MTV veejay about the lack of black artists being featured on the channel despite the successes of Jackson and Prince.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} \n\nWhen MTV and [[BET]] both avoided playing the video for \"Loosey's Rap\" because of its graphic sexual content, James considered the networks hypocritical in light of them still playing provocative videos by artists such as [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Decline ===\nIn 1989, James's 11th album, ''[[Kickin' (Rick James album)|Kickin'<nowiki/>]]'', was released only in the UK. By 1990, he had lost his deal with Warner Bros. and James began struggling with personal and legal troubles. That year [[MC Hammer]] released his hit [[signature song]], \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\", which sampled the prominent opening riff from \"[[Super Freak]].\" James and his co-writer on \"[[Super Freak]],\" Alonzo Miller, successfully sued Hammer for shared songwriting credit and all three consequently received a Grammy Award for Best R&B Song in 1991.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 20, 1990|title=M.C. Hammer Says He Will Pay Rick James For 'Borrowed' Song|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_a8DAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=rick+james+jet#v=onepage&q=rick%20james%20&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=34|via=}}</ref>{{sfn|James|2014|p=296}} \n\nIn 1997, James released ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'', his first album since his release from prison on assault charges, and he toured to promote the album. That same year, he discussed his life and career in interviews for the [[VH1]] musical documentary series, ''[[Behind the Music]]'', which aired in early 1998. James's musical career slowed again after he suffered a minor stroke during a concert in 1998.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/b734c5d05c630152d9a395674b02c7ca|title=Singer Rick James Suffers Stroke|last=Wilson|first=Jeff|date=November 10, 1998|agency=Associated Press|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> He was featured on the song \"Love Gravy\" with [[Ike Turner]] for the 1998 soundtrack album ''[[Chef Aid: The South Park Album]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1998-11-24-1998328047-story.html|title=Not for the faint of heart Review: You'll be happy to know star-studded 'Chef Aid' lives down to the tastelessness of 'South Park.'|last=Considine|first=J. D.|date=November 24, 1998|website=The Baltimore Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James accepted an offer by Eddie Murphy to appear in the comedy-drama ''[[Life (1999 film)|Life]]'' (1999)''.''{{sfn|James|2014|p=317}}\n\n===Resurgence<!--I'm Rick James bitch links here-->===\n\n====''Chappelle's Show''====\nIn early 2004, after years out of the spotlight, James participated in a [[Sketch comedy|comedy sketch]] on ''[[Chappelle's Show]]'', in a segment called \"Charlie Murphy's True Hollywood Stories.\" James and [[Charlie Murphy|Murphy]] recounted humorous stories of their experiences together during the early 1980s. During the sketch, James's character, played by [[Dave Chappelle]], utters the now famous catchphrase, \"I'm Rick James, bitch!\" The sketches were punctuated by James, explaining his past behavior with the phrase, \"cocaine is a hell of a drug!\"\n\nJames enjoyed a career revival after his appearance on the show. He supported Teena Marie's tour of her album ''La Do\u00f1a'' and toured with her in May 2004; playing with her at the [[KBLX-FM|KBLX]] Stone Soul Picnic, [[Pioneer Amphitheatre]], [[Hayward, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/rick-james-performs-at-the-7th-annual-stone-soul-picnic-on-news-photo/51149124|title=Rick James Performs at the 7Th Annual Stone Soul Picnic\u2026 Nieuwsfoto's &#124; Getty Images Nederland &#124; 51149124|date=May 31, 2004|publisher=Gettyimages.com|accessdate=2012-04-13}}</ref> James gave his last performance at the 4th annual [[BET Awards]] on June 29, 2004. He performed a live rendition of \"Fire & Desire\" with Teena Marie. James called out a girl backstage who didn't recognize him by saying, \"never mind who you thought I was, I'm Rick James, bitch!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/14912/20141108/5-shocking-hip-hop-award-show-moments-rick-james-suge.htm|title=5 Shocking Hip-Hop Award Show Moments: Rick James, Suge Knight, Diana Ross And More [WATCH]|date=November 8, 2014 |website=Music Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Autobiography ===\nAt the time of his death, James was working on an autobiography, ''[[The Confessions of Rick James|The Confessions of Rick James: Memoirs of a Super Freak]]'', as well as a new album. The book was finally published in 2007 by Colossus Books and features a picture of his tombstone. Noted music journalist/biographer [[David Ritz]], who had been employed by James to work on the book with him, later said that this version did not truly reflect how the musician wanted it published. In 2014, Ritz published his own, re-edited version, ''Glow: The Autobiography of Rick James''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2014/07/07/glow-the-autobiography-of-rick-james/11927085/|title=Autobiography 'Glow' is bright with Rick James' legacy|last=Seymour|first=Gene|date=July 7, 2014|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Relationships and children===\nJames had two children with Syville Morgan, a former singer and songwriter. They had a daughter, Tyenza, and a son, Rick Jr.\n\nJames dated actress [[Linda Blair]] from 1982 to 1984. They met after James read an interview where Blair called him sexy. He contacted her and spent time getting to know the actress during a short stint living at the [[Chateau Marmont]] in [[Hollywood]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/despite-a-frightening-collapse-funkstar-rick-james-wont-let-anyone-rein-him-in-vol-18-no-21/|title=Despite a Frightening Collapse, Funkstar Rick James Won't Let Anyone Rein Him in|last=Levin|first=Eric|date=November 22, 1982|website=People|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Early in their relationship Blair became pregnant and [[Abortion|aborted]] the fetus. James wrote in his memoir, \"I loved Linda and it hurt me that she would choose to abort our child without even wanting to talk to me about it first. I still look back on her choice with sadness and wonder about our baby, and how having that child might have changed my life.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Confessions of Rick James: Memoirs of a Super Freak|last=James|first=Rick|publisher=Colossus Books|year=2007|isbn=9780979097638|location=Phoenix|pages=|oclc=153931750}}</ref> His hit song \"[[Cold Blooded (song)|Cold Blooded]]\" was about his relationship with Blair. \"It was about how Linda could freeze my blood,\" he wrote in his memoir.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1989, James met 17-year-old party-goer Tanya Hijazi. The two began a romance in 1990. In 1993, the couple had their only child and James's youngest, Tazman. Following their respective releases from prison for assaulting Mary Sauger and Frances Alley,<ref name=\"MORAN\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-31/local/me-29801_1_rick-james|title=Woman Recounts Tale of Abuse at James Trial: Court: She says singer and his girlfriend beat her unconscious and revived her for further mistreatment. He faces life in prison if convicted on all charges.|last=Moran|first=Julio|date=August 31, 1993|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-08-03/local/me-242_1_rick-james|title=Pop Singer Arrested on Torture, Drug Charges: Violence: Grammy-winner Rick James and a girlfriend are accused of imprisoning a woman at his Mulholland Drive home.|first1=Aaron|last1=Curtiss|first2=Jack|last2=Cheevers |lastauthoramp=y|date=August 3, 1991 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> they married in 1996 and divorced in 2002.\n\nJames was very close with [[Teena Marie]], whom he met and began collaborating with in 1979. Teena Marie stated they were engaged \"for two weeks.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2010/12/28/top-10-little-known-facts-about-teena-marie/ |title=Top 10 little known facts about Teena Marie |work=CNN Entertainment |date=December 28, 2010 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Their professional partnership lasted into 2004, when Marie released her comeback album, ''[[La Do\u00f1a (album)|La Do\u00f1a]]'', which included her and James's duet \"I Got You\". When James died, Teena Marie said she was \"devastated by his death\" and struggled with a painkiller addiction following his passing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/teena-marie-ivory-queen-of-soul-dies-1.911215 |title=Teena Marie, Ivory Queen of Soul, dies |work=CBC News |date=December 27, 2010 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Friendships===\nJames enjoyed a close friendship with [[Eddie Murphy]], whom he met in 1981. He was also close to Murphy's older brother [[Charlie Murphy]], who worked as a security guard for his brother. James and Charlie Murphy talked about their relationship on Chapelle's Show. Charlie said he had a strained relationship with James. James said he used to start impromptu fights with Charlie and stain Murphy's couch with mud. \n\nJames was good friends with actress [[Debbie Allen]]. Allen once invited James to a Broadway show and he fell asleep due to exhaustion from his sexual activities. After the show she confronted him in the dressing room. She pinned him down and pleaded that he was throwing his life away. \"All you do is get high and have sex,\" she said. He promised to change his ways, but he broke his promise that same night.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nJames was also a friend of fellow Motown act performers [[Smokey Robinson]] and [[Marvin Gaye]], singers James idolized as a teenager. Additionally, he befriended Gaye's second wife, Janis, and he was godfather of Gaye's daughter [[Nona Gaye|Nona]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2005/10/11/acting-singing-the-gospel-truth-for-nona-gaye/|title=Acting, singing the 'Gospel' truth for Nona Gaye|last=Wilson-Combs|first=Lana K.|date=2005-10-11|website=East Bay Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James's relationship with Robinson began shortly after James signed with Motown and, in 1983, the duo recorded the hit \"Ebony Eyes\".\n\nJames also idolized former Temptations lead singer [[David Ruffin]] and Ruffin's self-proclaimed cousin, bass vocalist [[Melvin Franklin]], and grabbed at the chance to produce the hit \"Standing on the Top\" for them in 1982. Before that, the then-current lineup of the group recorded background vocals on two James-associated projects\u2014James's ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'' (singing \"Ghetto Life\" and \"[[Super Freak]]\") and Teena Marie's ''[[It Must Be Magic]]'' (singing on the title track). In \"Super Freak\", \"It Must Be Magic\", and \"[[Standing On The Top (song)|Standing On The Top]]\", James famously shouted out, \"Temptations, SING!\"{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n===Drug abuse and health problems===\nJames' [[Substance dependence|drug abuse]] began in his teens, first with [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and [[heroin]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> He began using [[cocaine]] in the late 1960s. His [[Cocaine dependence|cocaine addiction]] increased by the 1980s, and he began [[Free base|freebasing]] by the end of the decade. When he smoked [[crack cocaine]] in his [[Beverly Hills]] mansion, he often put aluminum foil on the windows to block onlookers.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James claimed that he quit cocaine when he entered prison, however, his autopsy showed there was a small amount of the drug in his bloodstream at the time of his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491032/rick-james-had-nine-different-drugs-in-his-system-when-he-died/|title=Rick James Had Nine Different Drugs In His System When He Died|work=MTV News |date=September 17, 2004 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis drug use led to major health problems. In April 1984, he was hospitalized after being found unconscious in the middle of his house by a friend.<ref name=hospital>{{citation |title=Singer Rick James Admitted to Buffalo, N.Y. Hospital |work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |date=April 30, 1984}}</ref> In 1998, James suffered a stroke after a blood vessel ruptured in his neck during a concert at [[Mile High Stadium]] in [[Denver]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Earlier that year he had [[hip replacement]] surgery to repair damage done \"from jumping around on stage and substance abuse.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Kidnapping and assault convictions===\nBy the 1990s, James' drug use was public knowledge. He was heavily addicted to cocaine and later admitted to spending about $7,000 per week on drugs for five years straight. In 1991, James and his girlfriend Tanya Hijazi were accused of holding 24-year-old Frances Alley hostage for up to six days, tying her up, forcing her to perform sexual acts, and burning her legs and abdomen with the hot end of a crack cocaine pipe during a week-long cocaine binge.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 19, 1991|title=Rick James, Girlfriend Are Accused Of Burning, Sexually Abusing Woman|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I7wDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=rick+james+jet+1991#v=onepage&q=rick%20james%20&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=60|via=}}</ref> James faced a maximum sentence of life in prison if convicted on all charges, which included [[assault]] with a deadly weapon, aggravated [[Mayhem (crime)|mayhem]], [[torture]], forcible [[Oral sex|oral copulation]], [[false imprisonment]] and [[kidnapping]].<ref name=\"MORAN\" />\n\nIn 1993, while out on bail for that incident, James, under the influence of cocaine, assaulted [[music executive]] Mary Sauger at the [[Sunset Tower|St. James Club and Hotel]] in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]]. Sauger claims she met James and Hijazi for a business meeting, but said the two then kidnapped and beat her over a 20-hour period.<ref name=\"MORAN\" />\n\nJames was found guilty of both offenses but was cleared of a torture charge that could have put him in prison for the rest of his life. While serving his five-year sentence at [[Folsom State Prison|Folsom Prison]], James lost a [[Lawsuit|civil suit]] to Sauger, who was awarded nearly $2 million in damages in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reprints.longform.org/rick-james-super-freak-sager |title=The Rise and Fall of a Super Freak |website=Reprints.longform.org |last=Sager |first=Mike |date= |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> James was ordered to pay her about $1 million; the hotel and a private security firm were found liable for nearly $750,000 in damages due to negligence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1994/12/09/Singer-Rick-James-victim-wins-18M/8534786949200/|title=Singer Rick James' victim wins $1.8M|last=|first=|date=December 9, 1994|website=UPI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James was released from prison in 1996 after serving more than two years.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.eonline.com/news/33502/rick-james-gets-out-of-jail-his-fianc-e-goes-in|title= Rick James Gets Out of Jail, His Fianc\u00e9e Goes In |first= Marcus |last=Errico |work=[[E!]] Online |date =  August 23, 1996 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1998, James was accused of [[sexual assault|sexually assaulting]] a 26-year-old woman, but the charges were later dropped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/73420/rick-james-denies-sex-assault-allegations|title=Rick James Denies Sex Assault Allegations|work=Billboard.com |date=November 18, 2002 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, James' estate was sued for $50 million by a woman who accused him of raping her when she was 15 years old at a group home for troubled youths in Buffalo, New York in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/02/14/rick-james-accused-of-raping-15-year-old-in-child-victims-act-lawsuit|title=Rick James accused of raping 15-year-old in Child Victims Act lawsuit|work=The Buffalo News |date=February 14, 2020 |accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-16/woman-who-says-rick-james-raped-her-in-1979-sues-estate|title=Woman who says Rick James raped her in 1979 sues estate|date=February 16, 2020|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn the morning of August 6, 2004, James' caretaker found him dead in his Los Angeles home at the Oakwood Toluca Hills apartment complex, just outside [[Burbank, California|Burbank]]. He had died from [[respiratory failure|pulmonary failure]] and [[cardiac failure]], associated with his various health conditions of [[diabetes]], a stroke, [[artificial pacemaker|pacemaker]], and heart attack. His autopsy found [[alprazolam]], [[diazepam]], [[bupropion]], [[citalopram]], [[hydrocodone]], [[digoxin]], [[chlorpheniramine]], [[methamphetamine]], and cocaine in his blood.<ref name=\"autopsy\">{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9905E4D61739F93BA2575AC0A9629C8B63 | work=The New York Times | title=Arts Briefing: Highlights; Rick James Autopsy Results | first=Ben | last=Sisario | date=September 18, 2004 | access-date=May 22, 2010}}</ref> However, the coroner stated that \"none of the drugs or drug combinations were found to be at levels that were life-threatening in and of themselves\".<ref name=\"autopsy\" />\n\nJames was buried at [[Forest Lawn Cemetery (Buffalo)|Forest Lawn Cemetery]] in Buffalo, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forest-lawn.com/famous-residents/rick-james|title=Rick James {{!}} Famous Residents {{!}} Forest Lawn Cemetery|last=|first=|date=|website=www.forest-lawn.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nJames received the following honors:\n\n* [[American Music Awards of 1982|1982]]: [[American Music Award for Favorite Soul/R&B Album]] (''Street Songs'')\n* 1996: Inducted into the Buffalo Music Hall of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1996/09/15/rick-james-adored-by-the-famous-and-obscure-buffalos-celebrated-son-mirrors-the-americacracked-tragedy/|title=Rick James Adored By The Famous And Obscure, Buffalo's Celebrated Son Mirrors The America Cracked Tragedy|last=Continelli|first=Louise|date=1996-09-15|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nJames was nominated for three Grammy Awards, winning one as a co-writer for MC Hammer's song \"U Can't Touch This\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1982\n| \"[[Super Freak]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male Rock Vocal Performance|Grammy Award for Best Rock Vocal Performance, Male]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1982\n| \"Street Songs\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1991\n| \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song]]\n| {{win}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Rick James discography}}James's entire Motown Records back catalogue was released in 2014 on [[iTunes]] for the first time in digitally [[remaster]]ed form. This marks the first time many of his albums have been widely available since their initial releases. Physical copies of James's albums, namely ''Fire It Up'', ''Garden of Love'' and ''The Flag'', have become rare and highly sought after by fans.\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Come Get It!]]'' <small>with The Stone City Band</small> (1978)\n* ''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fire It Up (Rick James album)|Fire It Up]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Garden of Love (album)|Garden of Love]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Throwin' Down]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Cold Blooded (Rick James album)|Cold Blooded]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Glow (Rick James album)|Glow]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[The Flag (album)|The Flag]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Wonderful (Rick James album)|Wonderful]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Kickin' (Rick James album)|Kickin']]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Deeper Still (album)|Deeper Still]]'' (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Benjaminson|first=Peter|year=2017|title=Super Freak: The Life of Rick James|publisher=Chicago Review Press, Inc.|isbn=9781613749579}}\n* {{cite book|last=Denisof|first=R. Serge|year=1988|title=Inside MTV|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-88738-864-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Durchholz|first=Daniel|year=2010|title=Neil Young: Long May You Run: The Illustrated History, Updated Edition|publisher=Voyageur Press|isbn=9781610604536}}\n* {{cite book|last=James|first=Rick|year=2014|title=Glow: The Autobiography of Rick James|publisher=Atria Books|isbn=978-1-4767-6416-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Rick James}}\n* {{Official website|www.rickjames.com|Rick James}} \u2013 official site\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0416872|name=Rick James}}\n* {{Find a Grave|9276693}}\n* [http://www.thrasherswheat.org/friends/rick-james.htm Rick James, The Mynah Birds and Neil Young]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130724021404/http://longform.org/stories/rise-and-fall-of-a-super-freak Rise & Fall of a Super Freak]\n\n{{Rick James}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Rick}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American expatriate musicians in Canada]]\n[[Category:American kidnappers]]\n[[Category:American funk bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American funk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American funk keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American funk singers]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American soul guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Cemetery, Buffalo]]\n[[Category:Cocaine-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Motown artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:A&M Records artists]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records artists]]\n[[Category:African-American rock singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American singer, songwriter, dancer, bandleader and record producer}}\n{{other uses|Rick James (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rick James\n| image              = Rick James in Lifestyles of the Rich 1984.JPG\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = James on ''[[Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous]]'' in 1984\n| birth_name         = James Ambrose Johnson Jr.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1948|2|1}}\n| birth_place        = [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| alias              = Ricky Matthews\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2004|8|6|1948|2|1}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Singing|Singer]]|[[Songwriter]]|[[Arrangement|Arranger]]|[[Record producer]]|[[Dance|Dancer]]}}\n| years_active       = 1964\u20132004\n| children           = 3\n| relatives          = \n| website            = {{URL|www.rickjames.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]|[[Soul music|soul]]|[[funk]]|[[funk rock]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Holden |first=Stephen |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/09/06/arts/punk-rock-rick-james.html |title=Punk Rock - Rick James |work=The New York Times |date=September 6, 1981 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jim |last=Sullivan |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1991-10-13/entertainment/9104020472_1_hard-core-punk-rock-heavy-metal |title=The Age of Hyphen-Rock |website=Chicago Tribune |date=October 13, 1991 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>|[[rock music|rock]]|[[doo-wop]]|[[dance-punk]]}}\n| instrument = Vocals, bass, guitar, keyboards, drums, other percussion instruments\n| label = {{hlist|[[Gordy Records|Gordy]]|[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]|[[A&M Records|A&M]]|[[Mercury Records|Mercury]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Mynah Birds]]|Stone City Band|Heaven and Earth|[[Mary Jane Girls]]|Process and the Doo Rags|[[Val Young]]|[[Eddie Murphy]]|[[Teena Marie]]}}\n  }}<!--end-module-->\n}}\n\n'''James Ambrose Johnson Jr.''' (February 1, 1948 \u2013 August 6, 2004), better known by his stage name '''Rick James''', was an American [[singer-songwriter]], [[multi-instrumentalist]] and [[Record producer|producer]]. Born and raised in [[Buffalo, New York]], James began his musical career in his teen years. He was in various bands before entering the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] and to avoid [[conscription|being drafted]] in 1964, James [[desertion|deserted]] to [[Toronto]], Canada, where he formed the rock band [[the Mynah Birds]], who eventually signed a recording deal with [[Motown|Motown Records]] in 1966. James' career with the group halted after military authorities discovered his whereabouts and eventually convicted James to a one-year prison term related to the draft charges. After being released, James moved to California where he started a variety of rock and funk groups in the late 1960s and early 1970s.\n\nAfter forming the locally popular Stone City Band in his hometown of Buffalo in 1977, James finally found success as a recording artist after signing with Motown's [[Gordy Records]], releasing the album ''[[Come Get It!]]'' in 1978 which produced the hits \"[[You and I (Rick James song)|You & I]]\" and \"[[Mary Jane (Rick James song)|Mary Jane]].\" In 1981, James released his most successful album, ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'', which included career-defining hits such as \"[[Give It to Me Baby]]\" and \"[[Super Freak]],\" the latter song becoming his biggest [[Crossover music|crossover single]], mixing elements of funk, disco, rock and [[new wave music|new wave]]. James was also known for his [[soul music|soulful]] ballads such as \"Fire & Desire\" and \"[[Ebony Eyes (Rick James song)|Ebony Eyes]].\" In addition, James also had a successful career as a songwriter and producer for other artists including [[Teena Marie]], the [[Mary Jane Girls]], [[the Temptations]], [[Eddie Murphy]] and [[Smokey Robinson]].\n\nJames' mainstream success had peaked with the release of his album ''[[Glow (Rick James album)|Glow]]'' in 1985 and his appearance on the popular TV show, ''[[The A-Team]]''. His subsequent album releases failed to sell as well as their predecessors. Rapper [[MC Hammer]] sampled James' \"Super Freak\" for his 1990 hit, \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\" which won [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song|Best R&B Song]] at the [[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|1991 Grammy Awards]]. James received his only Grammy for composing the song.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/rick-james|title=Rick James|website=Recording Academy Grammy Awards|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> By the early 1990s, James' career was hampered by his drug addiction and he was embroiled with legal issues. In 1993, James was convicted for two separate instances of kidnapping and torturing two different women while under the influence of [[crack cocaine]], resulting in a three-year sentence at [[Folsom State Prison]]. James was released on parole in 1996 and released the album ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'' in 1997. James's health problems halted his career again after he had a mild stroke during a concert in 1998, and he announced a semi-retirement.\n\nIn 2004, James's career returned to mainstream [[Popular culture|pop culture]] after he appeared in an episode of ''[[Chappelle's Show]]''. The segment involved a [[Charlie Murphy]] ''[[E! True Hollywood Story|True Hollywood Stories]]''-style skit that satirized James' wild lifestyle in the 1980s. This resulted in renewed interest in his music and that year he returned to perform on the road. James died later that year from [[heart failure]] at age 56.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n=== Early life ===\nJohnson was born on February 1, 1948, in [[Buffalo, New York]], to Mabel (n\u00e9e Sims) and James Ambrose Johnson Sr. He was one of eight children. James's father, an autoworker, left the family when James was 10. His mother was a dancer for [[Katherine Dunham]], and later worked as a [[Numbers game|numbers-runner]] to earn a living.<ref name=\"glowreview\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/05/rick-james-reveled-in-super-freaky-autobiography-i-was-caligula/ |title=Rick James' insane life of sex, drugs and music |last=Getlen |first=Larry |date=July 5, 2014 |work=[[New York Post]] |accessdate=November 17, 2014}}</ref> James's mother would take him on her collecting route, and it was in bars where she worked that James saw performers such as [[John Coltrane]], [[Miles Davis]], and [[Etta James]] perform.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James claimed later, in the autobiography ''Glow'', that he lost his virginity at \"age 9 or 10\" to a 14-year-old local girl, claiming his \"kinky nature came in early.\"<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James eventually attended [[Orchard Park High School]] and [[Bennett High School (Buffalo, New York)|Bennett High School]] prior to dropping out. James was introduced to drugs at an early age and was busted for burglary as a young teen.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> Due to his stints in jail for theft, James entered the [[United States Navy]] at 14 or 15, lying about his age, to avoid the [[Conscription in the United States#Vietnam|draft]]. During that time, he also became a drummer for local jazz groups in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> Due to him missing his twice-monthly [[United States Navy Reserve|Reserve]] sessions aboard {{USS|Enterprise|CVN-65|6}}, he found himself ordered to Vietnam.<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\n=== Early career ===\nIn 1964, James fled to [[Toronto]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book |title=Glow: The autobiography of Rick James|last=James|first=Rick|publisher=Atria Books|last2=Ritz |first2=David|lastauthoramp=y|year=2014|isbn=9781476764146|edition=First hardcover|location=New York|pages=|oclc=862348461}}</ref> Soon after his arrival three drunk white men tried to jump him outside a club; a trio of other guys came to his aid. One of the men who came to his aid was [[Levon Helm]], who at the time was an undiscovered member of [[Ronnie Hawkins]]' backing band.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/07/rick-james-memoir-moments-glow.html|title=The 12 Most Rick James\u2013y Moments in Rick James's New Memoir, Glow|last=Carley|first=Brennan|date=July 11, 2014|website=Vulture|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> He invited James to their show later that night and he ended up performing onstage with them.<ref name=\":0\" />  In Toronto James made friends with local musicians [[Neil Young]] and [[Joni Mitchell]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> To avoid being caught by military authorities, James went under the assumed name, \"Ricky James Matthews\".<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> That same year, James formed [[the Mynah Birds]], a band that produced a fusion of [[Soul music|soul]], [[Folk music|folk]] and [[rock music]]. In 1965, the band briefly recorded for the Canadian division of [[Columbia Records]], releasing the single, \"Mynah Bird Hop\"/\"Mynah Bird Song\". At one point, [[Nick St. Nicholas]] of later [[Steppenwolf (band)|Steppenwolf]] fame was a member; eventually bassist [[Bruce Palmer]] replaced him by the time \"Mynah Bird Hop\" was recorded. James and Palmer recruited guitarists Tom Morgan and Xavier Taylor and drummer Rick Mason to form a new Mynah Birds lineup, and soon traveled to [[Detroit]] to record with [[Motown]]. Before the group began recording their first songs for the label, Morgan left, unhappy about the label's attitude towards the musicians. Neil Young eventually took his place. It was while in Detroit that James met his musical heroes, [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Stevie Wonder]]. After meeting Wonder and telling him his name, Wonder felt the name \"Ricky James Matthews\" was \"too long\", and instead told James to shorten it to \"Ricky James\".<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\nIn 1966, a financial dispute in Toronto between James and the Mynah Birds' handler, Morley Shelman<ref name=\"Benjaminson, p. 42\">Benjaminson, p. 42</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org/2012/04/mynah-birds-in-depth-exclusive.html|title=Neil Young News: The Mynah Birds: An In Depth Exclusive|website=neilyoungnews.thrasherswheat.org}}</ref><ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\">Durchholz, p. 23</ref> led to Motown's learning of James's fugitive status with the Navy. Hoping to preempt any scrutiny, Motown execs told Rick they would not be releasing any more of his material and \"convinced\" him to come back and work with them after straightening out his legal issues.<ref name=\"Benjaminson, p. 42\"/><ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\"/> James surrendered himself to the [[FBI]], and, in May 1966, was sentenced by the Navy to five months' hard labor for \"Unauthorized Absence\". He was not yet 19 years old. James escaped from the Brooklyn Naval Brig after only six weeks' confinement, but following another six months [[Fugitive|on the lam]], surrendered himself a second time. With help from his mother, James found legal assistance from his cousin, future Congressman [[Louis Stokes]] and an attorney, former Marine Captain John Bracken, who pled James' second [[court-martial]] down from a potential five years' hard labor to five months.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /><ref>Benjaminson, pp. 43-47</ref> After his release from [[Portsmouth Naval Prison]] in August 1967, James returned to Toronto<ref>Benjaminson, pp. 47-48</ref> and endured another detention, initially derailing resumption of his career with Mynah Bird bandmate [[Neil Merryweather]], with whom he would later collaborate, first at Motown and then in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"Durchholz, p. 23\"/><ref>Bejaminson pp. 50, 53</ref>\n\nIn 1968, again working under the pseudonym Ricky Matthews, James produced and wrote songs at Motown for acts such as [[The Miracles]], [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]], and [[The Spinners (American R&B group)|The Spinners]]. According to James, he briefly got involved in [[procuring (prostitution)|pimp activity]] during this time, but stopped because he felt he was not qualified for it due to the harsh activity and the abuse of women there.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> It was during this third stint at Motown that James met musician [[Greg Reeves]]. Reeves, hoping to find a better situation than the [[United States dollar|US$]]38 a week (US${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|85|1968}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}}) he was earning as a session bassist for [[Berry Gordy]], joined James, looking to \"hitch a lift from Neil Young's rising star,\" and relocated to Los Angeles.<ref>Bejaminson pp. 56</ref> \n\nOn one of his first night in Los Angeles, James was crashing on musician [[Stephen Stills]]' couch. When he awoke he saw a stoned young man sitting on the floor in the [[lotus position]]. The man's wrists were bleeding so a scared James sought help. James was later formally introduced to the man who was [[Jim Morrison]], lead singer of [[the Doors]]. After the Doors opened for [[Buffalo Springfield]] at the [[Whisky a Go Go]], Morrison tricked James into taking [[Acid (drug)|acid]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn California, James initially worked as a duo with Greg Reeves, but soon after James introduced Reeves to Neil Young, it was Reeves, not James, who was hired as bassist for the newly formed rock [[Supergroup (music)|supergroup]], [[Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /><ref name=\"nickwarburton.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nickwarburton.com/wordpress/?cat=7|title=Rick James's Early Years|website=nickwarburton.com |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Around this time James formed several versions of the rock band Salt'N'Pepper<ref name=\"nickwarburton.com\" /> and got involved with [[Hairdresser|hair stylist]] [[Jay Sebring]], who agreed to invest in his music.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> In 1969, James claimed that Sebring invited him to attend a party at actress [[Sharon Tate]]\u2019s house, but he was too [[Hangover|hungover]] to get out of bed. The next morning he discovered that Sebring had been [[Tate murders|murdered]] when he saw the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' headline \"Sharon Tate, Four Others Murdered.\"<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1970, James and Salt'N'Pepper member Ed Roth later were included in Bruce Palmer's solo album ''[[The Cycle Is Complete|The Cycle is Complete]]''. The duo also recorded as part of the group Heaven and Earth in Toronto. Heaven and Earth eventually changed their name to Great White Cane and recorded a self-titled album for the Los Angeles label Lion Records, released in 1972. James formed another band, Hot Lips, afterwards.\n\n=== Solo career ===\nIn 1973, James signed with [[A&M Records]], where his first single under the name Rick James, \"My Mama\", was released in 1974, becoming a club hit in Europe.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> \n\nIn 1976, James returned to Buffalo, New York, and formed the Stone City Band and recorded the song \"Get Up and Dance!\", which was his second single to be released. In 1977, James and the Stone City Band signed a contract with Motown's Gordy Records imprint, where they began recording their first album in New York City.\n\nIn April 1978, James released his debut solo album, ''[[Come Get It!]]'', which included the Stone City Band. The album launched the top 20 hit, \"[[You and I (Rick James song)|You and I]]\", which became his first number-one R&B hit. The album also included the hit single, \"[[Mary Jane (Rick James song)|Mary Jane]]\". It eventually sold two million copies, launching James's musical career to stardom, and helping out Motown Records at a time when label fortunes had dwindled.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Bob|url=https://archive.org/details/michaeljacksonma00jone|url-access=registration|quote=sold over 1 million copies. Street Songs.|title=Michael Jackson, the Man Behind the Mask: An Insider's Story of the King of Pop|last2=Brown|first2=Stacy|date=2005|publisher=Select Books Inc.|isbn=978-1-59079-072-4|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/michaeljacksonma00jone/page/42 42]|language=en}}</ref> In early 1979, James's second album, ''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]'', followed the previous album's success, eventually selling a million copies. A third album, ''[[Fire It Up (Rick James album)|Fire It Up]]'', was released in late 1979 going [[Recording Industry Association of America certification|gold]]. Around that same period, James launched his first headlining tour, the Fire It Up Tour, and agreed to invite the then-upcoming artist, [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], as well as singer [[Teena Marie]], as his opening act.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James had produced Marie's successful Motown debut album, ''[[Wild and Peaceful (Teena Marie album)|Wild and Peaceful]]'' and was featured on the hit duet, \"I'm a Sucker (For Your Love)\". James was credited with naming Marie, \"Lady Tee\", on the song, a nickname that stuck with Marie for the rest of her career. The Fire It Up tour led to James developing a bitter rivalry with Prince, after he accused the musician of ripping off his act.<ref name=\"glowreview\" />\n\n{{listen\n| Type           = single\n| filename       = Rick James - Super Freak excerpt.ogg\n| format         = [[Ogg]]\n| title          = \"Super Freak\"}}\n\nFollowing the end of the tour in 1980, James released the ballads-heavy ''[[Garden of Love (album)|Garden of Love]]'', which became his fourth gold record. In 1981, James recorded his best-selling album to date, ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'', which like his previous four albums, was a [[concept album]]. ''Street Songs'' featured a fusion mix of different genres, including rock and [[new wave music|new wave]], as well as James's brand of crossover funk, enabling James's own style of \"punk funk\". The album featured hit singles such as \"[[Ghetto Life (song)|Ghetto Life]]\", the Teena Marie duet \"Fire and Desire\", \"[[Give It to Me Baby]]\", and his biggest crossover hit to date, \"[[Super Freak]]\", which peaked at number 16 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and sold over 1 million copies. ''Street Songs'' peaked at number one R&B and number three pop, and sold over 3 million copies alone in the United States.<ref name=\":4\" /> Following up that success, James released two more gold albums, 1982's ''[[Throwin' Down]]'' and 1983's ''[[Cold Blooded (Rick James album)|Cold Blooded]]''.\n\nDuring this period, envious of Prince's success as producer of other acts including [[The Time (band)|The Time]] and [[Vanity 6]], James launched the acts Process and the Doo-Rags, and the [[Mary Jane Girls]], featuring his former background singer Joanne \"JoJo\" McDuffie as the lead vocalist and background performer, finding success with the latter group, due to the hits, \"[[All Night Long (Mary Jane Girls song)|All Night Long]]\", \"Candy Man\", and \"[[In My House]]\". In 1982, James produced the Temptations' Top 10 R&B hit, \"[[Standing On The Top (song)|Standing On The Top]]\". In 1983, James recorded the hit duet, \"Ebony Eyes\", with singer [[Smokey Robinson]], as well as a ballad \"Tell Me What You Want\" with an introduction by Billy Dee Williams. In 1985, James produced another hit for entertainer [[Eddie Murphy]] with the song \"[[Party All the Time]]\". That same year he appeared on an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]'' with [[Isaac Hayes]]. After the release of his ninth solo album, ''[[The Flag (album)|The Flag]]'', in 1986, James signed with [[Warner Bros. Records]], which released the album ''[[Wonderful (Rick James album)|Wonderful]]'' in 1988, featuring the hit, \"Loosey's Rap\".\n\nJames's controversial and provocative image became troublesome sometimes. Famous for promoting the use of [[marijuana]] live in concerts during a time that simple possession could lead to a long term prison sentence, James was often threatened by cops in various cities that he would be arrested if he smoked marijuana on stage during performances of songs such as \"Fire It Up\" and \"Mary Jane\". According to Kerry Gordy, most Motown executives erroneously thought the latter song was a \"simple cute love song to a girl\" not knowing the song was about marijuana.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nJames' overtly sexual bravado made it tough for him to be a bigger mainstream act. After the debut of the fledgling music video network [[MTV]] in August of 1981, James tried to present the music video to \"Super Freak\" to the label, only for the channel to turn the video down. James accused the network of racism.{{sfn|Denisof|1988|pp=69\u201371}} MTV denied this, stating the real reason \"Super Freak\" was turned down by MTV was because they felt James' video was too vulgar for the channel. When younger artists such as Prince and [[Michael Jackson]] found fame on the channel, James accused the two singers of being \"tokens\" in a 1983 interview, demanding that any black artist that has a video aired on MTV take their video off the channel in protest. James' rant was cosigned by [[David Bowie]], who argued with an MTV veejay about the lack of black artists being featured on the channel despite the successes of Jackson and Prince.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}} \n\nWhen MTV and [[BET]] both avoided playing the video for \"Loosey's Rap\" because of its graphic sexual content, James considered the networks hypocritical in light of them still playing provocative videos by artists such as [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Decline ===\nIn 1989, James's 11th album, ''[[Kickin' (Rick James album)|Kickin'<nowiki/>]]'', was released only in the UK. By 1990, he had lost his deal with Warner Bros. and James began struggling with personal and legal troubles. That year [[MC Hammer]] released his hit [[signature song]], \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\", which sampled the prominent opening riff from \"[[Super Freak]].\" James and his co-writer on \"[[Super Freak]],\" Alonzo Miller, successfully sued Hammer for shared songwriting credit and all three consequently received a Grammy Award for Best R&B Song in 1991.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 20, 1990|title=M.C. Hammer Says He Will Pay Rick James For 'Borrowed' Song|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_a8DAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=rick+james+jet#v=onepage&q=rick%20james%20&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=34|via=}}</ref>{{sfn|James|2014|p=296}} \n\nIn 1997, James released ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'', his first album since his release from prison on assault charges, and he toured to promote the album. That same year, he discussed his life and career in interviews for the [[VH1]] musical documentary series, ''[[Behind the Music]]'', which aired in early 1998. James's musical career slowed again after he suffered a minor stroke during a concert in 1998.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://apnews.com/b734c5d05c630152d9a395674b02c7ca|title=Singer Rick James Suffers Stroke|last=Wilson|first=Jeff|date=November 10, 1998|agency=Associated Press|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> He was featured on the song \"Love Gravy\" with [[Ike Turner]] for the 1998 soundtrack album ''[[Chef Aid: The South Park Album]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1998-11-24-1998328047-story.html|title=Not for the faint of heart Review: You'll be happy to know star-studded 'Chef Aid' lives down to the tastelessness of 'South Park.'|last=Considine|first=J. D.|date=November 24, 1998|website=The Baltimore Sun|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James accepted an offer by Eddie Murphy to appear in the comedy-drama ''[[Life (1999 film)|Life]]'' (1999)''.''{{sfn|James|2014|p=317}}\n\n===Resurgence<!--I'm Rick James bitch links here-->===\n\n====''Chappelle's Show''====\nIn early 2004, after years out of the spotlight, James participated in a [[Sketch comedy|comedy sketch]] on ''[[Chappelle's Show]]'', in a segment called \"Charlie Murphy's True Hollywood Stories.\" James and [[Charlie Murphy|Murphy]] recounted humorous stories of their experiences together during the early 1980s. During the sketch, James's character, played by [[Dave Chappelle]], utters the now famous catchphrase, \"I'm Rick James, bitch!\" The sketches were punctuated by James, explaining his past behavior with the phrase, \"cocaine is a hell of a drug!\"\n\nJames enjoyed a career revival after his appearance on the show. He supported Teena Marie's tour of her album ''La Do\u00f1a'' and toured with her in May 2004; playing with her at the [[KBLX-FM|KBLX]] Stone Soul Picnic, [[Pioneer Amphitheatre]], [[Hayward, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/rick-james-performs-at-the-7th-annual-stone-soul-picnic-on-news-photo/51149124|title=Rick James Performs at the 7Th Annual Stone Soul Picnic\u2026 Nieuwsfoto's &#124; Getty Images Nederland &#124; 51149124|date=May 31, 2004|publisher=Gettyimages.com|accessdate=2012-04-13}}</ref> James gave his last performance at the 4th annual [[BET Awards]] on June 29, 2004. He performed a live rendition of \"Fire & Desire\" with Teena Marie. James called out a girl backstage who didn't recognize him by saying, \"never mind who you thought I was, I'm Rick James, bitch!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musictimes.com/articles/14912/20141108/5-shocking-hip-hop-award-show-moments-rick-james-suge.htm|title=5 Shocking Hip-Hop Award Show Moments: Rick James, Suge Knight, Diana Ross And More [WATCH]|date=November 8, 2014 |website=Music Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Autobiography ===\nAt the time of his death, James was working on an autobiography, ''[[The Confessions of Rick James|The Confessions of Rick James: Memoirs of a Super Freak]]'', as well as a new album. The book was finally published in 2007 by Colossus Books and features a picture of his tombstone. Noted music journalist/biographer [[David Ritz]], who had been employed by James to work on the book with him, later said that this version did not truly reflect how the musician wanted it published. In 2014, Ritz published his own, re-edited version, ''Glow: The Autobiography of Rick James''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2014/07/07/glow-the-autobiography-of-rick-james/11927085/|title=Autobiography 'Glow' is bright with Rick James' legacy|last=Seymour|first=Gene|date=July 7, 2014|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Relationships and children===\nJames had two children with Syville Morgan, a former singer and songwriter. They had a daughter, Tyenza, and a son, Rick Jr.\n\nJames dated actress [[Linda Blair]] from 1982 to 1984. They met after James read an interview where Blair called him sexy. He contacted her and spent time getting to know the actress during a short stint living at the [[Chateau Marmont]] in [[Hollywood]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/despite-a-frightening-collapse-funkstar-rick-james-wont-let-anyone-rein-him-in-vol-18-no-21/|title=Despite a Frightening Collapse, Funkstar Rick James Won't Let Anyone Rein Him in|last=Levin|first=Eric|date=November 22, 1982|website=People|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Early in their relationship Blair became pregnant and [[Abortion|aborted]] the fetus. James wrote in his memoir, \"I loved Linda and it hurt me that she would choose to abort our child without even wanting to talk to me about it first. I still look back on her choice with sadness and wonder about our baby, and how having that child might have changed my life.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Confessions of Rick James: Memoirs of a Super Freak|last=James|first=Rick|publisher=Colossus Books|year=2007|isbn=9780979097638|location=Phoenix|pages=|oclc=153931750}}</ref> His hit song \"[[Cold Blooded (song)|Cold Blooded]]\" was about his relationship with Blair. \"It was about how Linda could freeze my blood,\" he wrote in his memoir.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1989, James met 17-year-old party-goer Tanya Hijazi. The two began a romance in 1990. In 1993, the couple had their only child and James's youngest, Tazman. Following their respective releases from prison for assaulting Mary Sauger and Frances Alley,<ref name=\"MORAN\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-08-31/local/me-29801_1_rick-james|title=Woman Recounts Tale of Abuse at James Trial: Court: She says singer and his girlfriend beat her unconscious and revived her for further mistreatment. He faces life in prison if convicted on all charges.|last=Moran|first=Julio|date=August 31, 1993|work=Los Angeles Times|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-08-03/local/me-242_1_rick-james|title=Pop Singer Arrested on Torture, Drug Charges: Violence: Grammy-winner Rick James and a girlfriend are accused of imprisoning a woman at his Mulholland Drive home.|first1=Aaron|last1=Curtiss|first2=Jack|last2=Cheevers |lastauthoramp=y|date=August 3, 1991 |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> they married in 1996 and divorced in 2002.\n\nJames was very close with [[Teena Marie]], whom he met and began collaborating with in 1979. Teena Marie stated they were engaged \"for two weeks.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://marquee.blogs.cnn.com/2010/12/28/top-10-little-known-facts-about-teena-marie/ |title=Top 10 little known facts about Teena Marie |work=CNN Entertainment |date=December 28, 2010 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref> Their professional partnership lasted into 2004, when Marie released her comeback album, ''[[La Do\u00f1a (album)|La Do\u00f1a]]'', which included her and James's duet \"I Got You\". When James died, Teena Marie said she was \"devastated by his death\" and struggled with a painkiller addiction following his passing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/teena-marie-ivory-queen-of-soul-dies-1.911215 |title=Teena Marie, Ivory Queen of Soul, dies |work=CBC News |date=December 27, 2010 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Friendships===\nJames enjoyed a close friendship with [[Eddie Murphy]], whom he met in 1981. He was also close to Murphy's older brother [[Charlie Murphy]], who worked as a security guard for his brother. James and Charlie Murphy talked about their relationship on Chapelle's Show. Charlie said he had a strained relationship with James. James said he used to start impromptu fights with Charlie and stain Murphy's couch with mud. \n\nJames was good friends with actress [[Debbie Allen]]. Allen once invited James to a Broadway show and he fell asleep due to exhaustion from his sexual activities. After the show she confronted him in the dressing room. She pinned him down and pleaded that he was throwing his life away. \"All you do is get high and have sex,\" she said. He promised to change his ways, but he broke his promise that same night.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nJames was also a friend of fellow Motown act performers [[Smokey Robinson]] and [[Marvin Gaye]], singers James idolized as a teenager. Additionally, he befriended Gaye's second wife, Janis, and he was godfather of Gaye's daughter [[Nona Gaye|Nona]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2005/10/11/acting-singing-the-gospel-truth-for-nona-gaye/|title=Acting, singing the 'Gospel' truth for Nona Gaye|last=Wilson-Combs|first=Lana K.|date=2005-10-11|website=East Bay Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James's relationship with Robinson began shortly after James signed with Motown and, in 1983, the duo recorded the hit \"Ebony Eyes\".\n\nJames also idolized former Temptations lead singer [[David Ruffin]] and Ruffin's self-proclaimed cousin, bass vocalist [[Melvin Franklin]], and grabbed at the chance to produce the hit \"Standing on the Top\" for them in 1982. Before that, the then-current lineup of the group recorded background vocals on two James-associated projects\u2014James's ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'' (singing \"Ghetto Life\" and \"[[Super Freak]]\") and Teena Marie's ''[[It Must Be Magic]]'' (singing on the title track). In \"Super Freak\", \"It Must Be Magic\", and \"[[Standing On The Top (song)|Standing On The Top]]\", James famously shouted out, \"Temptations, SING!\"{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n===Drug abuse and health problems===\nJames' [[Substance dependence|drug abuse]] began in his teens, first with [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] and [[heroin]].<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> He began using [[cocaine]] in the late 1960s. His [[Cocaine dependence|cocaine addiction]] increased by the 1980s, and he began [[Free base|freebasing]] by the end of the decade. When he smoked [[crack cocaine]] in his [[Beverly Hills]] mansion, he often put aluminum foil on the windows to block onlookers.<ref name=\"glowreview\" /> James claimed that he quit cocaine when he entered prison, however, his autopsy showed there was a small amount of the drug in his bloodstream at the time of his death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491032/rick-james-had-nine-different-drugs-in-his-system-when-he-died/|title=Rick James Had Nine Different Drugs In His System When He Died|work=MTV News |date=September 17, 2004 |access-date=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHis drug use led to major health problems. In April 1984, he was hospitalized after being found unconscious in the middle of his house by a friend.<ref name=hospital>{{citation |title=Singer Rick James Admitted to Buffalo, N.Y. Hospital |work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |date=April 30, 1984}}</ref> In 1998, James suffered a stroke after a blood vessel ruptured in his neck during a concert at [[Mile High Stadium]] in [[Denver]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Earlier that year he had [[hip replacement]] surgery to repair damage done \"from jumping around on stage and substance abuse.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n===Kidnapping and assault convictions===\nBy the 1990s, James' drug use was public knowledge. He was heavily addicted to cocaine and later admitted to spending about $7,000 per week on drugs for five years straight. In 1991, James and his girlfriend Tanya Hijazi were accused of holding 24-year-old Frances Alley hostage for up to six days, tying her up, forcing her to perform sexual acts, and burning her legs and abdomen with the hot end of a crack cocaine pipe during a week-long cocaine binge.<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=August 19, 1991|title=Rick James, Girlfriend Are Accused Of Burning, Sexually Abusing Woman|url=https://books.google.com/?id=I7wDAAAAMBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=rick+james+jet+1991#v=onepage&q=rick%20james%20&f=false|journal=Jet|volume=|pages=60|via=}}</ref> James faced a maximum sentence of life in prison if convicted on all charges, which included [[assault]] with a deadly weapon, aggravated [[Mayhem (crime)|mayhem]], [[torture]], forcible [[Oral sex|oral copulation]], [[false imprisonment]] and [[kidnapping]].<ref name=\"MORAN\" />\n\nIn 1993, while out on bail for that incident, James, under the influence of cocaine, assaulted [[music executive]] Mary Sauger at the [[Sunset Tower|St. James Club and Hotel]] in [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]]. Sauger claims she met James and Hijazi for a business meeting, but said the two then kidnapped and beat her over a 20-hour period.<ref name=\"MORAN\" />\n\nJames was found guilty of both offenses but was cleared of a torture charge that could have put him in prison for the rest of his life. While serving his five-year sentence at [[Folsom State Prison|Folsom Prison]], James lost a [[Lawsuit|civil suit]] to Sauger, who was awarded nearly $2 million in damages in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reprints.longform.org/rick-james-super-freak-sager |title=The Rise and Fall of a Super Freak |website=Reprints.longform.org |last=Sager |first=Mike |date= |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> James were ordered to pay her about $1 million; the hotel and a private security firm were found liable for nearly $750,000 in damages due to negligence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1994/12/09/Singer-Rick-James-victim-wins-18M/8534786949200/|title=Singer Rick James' victim wins $1.8M|last=|first=|date=December 9, 1994|website=UPI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref> James was released from prison in 1996 after serving more than two years.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.eonline.com/news/33502/rick-james-gets-out-of-jail-his-fianc-e-goes-in|title= Rick James Gets Out of Jail, His Fianc\u00e9e Goes In |first= Marcus |last=Errico |work=[[E!]] Online |date =  August 23, 1996 }}</ref> \n\nIn 1998, James was accused of [[sexual assault|sexually assaulting]] a 26-year-old woman, but the charges were later dropped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/73420/rick-james-denies-sex-assault-allegations|title=Rick James Denies Sex Assault Allegations|work=Billboard.com |date=November 18, 2002 |accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, James' estate was sued for $50 million by a woman who accused him of raping her when she was 15 years old at a group home for troubled youths in Buffalo, New York in 1979.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2020/02/14/rick-james-accused-of-raping-15-year-old-in-child-victims-act-lawsuit|title=Rick James accused of raping 15-year-old in Child Victims Act lawsuit|work=The Buffalo News |date=February 14, 2020 |accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-16/woman-who-says-rick-james-raped-her-in-1979-sues-estate|title=Woman who says Rick James raped her in 1979 sues estate|date=February 16, 2020|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn the morning of August 6, 2004, James' caretaker found him dead in his Los Angeles home at the Oakwood Toluca Hills apartment complex, just outside [[Burbank, California|Burbank]]. He had died from [[respiratory failure|pulmonary failure]] and [[cardiac failure]], associated with his various health conditions of [[diabetes]], a stroke, [[artificial pacemaker|pacemaker]], and heart attack. His autopsy found [[alprazolam]], [[diazepam]], [[bupropion]], [[citalopram]], [[hydrocodone]], [[digoxin]], [[chlorpheniramine]], [[methamphetamine]], and cocaine in his blood.<ref name=\"autopsy\">{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9905E4D61739F93BA2575AC0A9629C8B63 | work=The New York Times | title=Arts Briefing: Highlights; Rick James Autopsy Results | first=Ben | last=Sisario | date=September 18, 2004 | access-date=May 22, 2010}}</ref> However, the coroner stated that \"none of the drugs or drug combinations were found to be at levels that were life-threatening in and of themselves\".<ref name=\"autopsy\" />\n\nJames was buried at [[Forest Lawn Cemetery (Buffalo)|Forest Lawn Cemetery]] in Buffalo, New York.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forest-lawn.com/famous-residents/rick-james|title=Rick James {{!}} Famous Residents {{!}} Forest Lawn Cemetery|last=|first=|date=|website=www.forest-lawn.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nJames received the following honors:\n\n* [[American Music Awards of 1982|1982]]: [[American Music Award for Favorite Soul/R&B Album]] (''Street Songs'')\n* 1996: Inducted into the Buffalo Music Hall of Fame<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/1996/09/15/rick-james-adored-by-the-famous-and-obscure-buffalos-celebrated-son-mirrors-the-americacracked-tragedy/|title=Rick James Adored By The Famous And Obscure, Buffalo's Celebrated Son Mirrors The America Cracked Tragedy|last=Continelli|first=Louise|date=1996-09-15|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nJames was nominated for three Grammy Awards, winning one as a co-writer for MC Hammer's song \"U Can't Touch This\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| 1982\n| \"[[Super Freak]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male Rock Vocal Performance|Grammy Award for Best Rock Vocal Performance, Male]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1982\n| \"Street Songs\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Male R&B Vocal Performance|Best R&B Vocal Performance, Male]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1991\n| \"[[U Can't Touch This]]\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best R&B Song]]\n| {{win}}\n{{end}}\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Rick James discography}}James's entire Motown Records back catalogue was released in 2014 on [[iTunes]] for the first time in digitally [[remaster]]ed form. This marks the first time many of his albums have been widely available since their initial releases. Physical copies of James's albums, namely ''Fire It Up'', ''Garden of Love'' and ''The Flag'', have become rare and highly sought after by fans.\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Come Get It!]]'' <small>with The Stone City Band</small> (1978)\n* ''[[Bustin' Out of L Seven]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Fire It Up (Rick James album)|Fire It Up]]'' (1979)\n* ''[[Garden of Love (album)|Garden of Love]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Street Songs (album)|Street Songs]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Throwin' Down]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[Cold Blooded (Rick James album)|Cold Blooded]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Glow (Rick James album)|Glow]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[The Flag (album)|The Flag]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Wonderful (Rick James album)|Wonderful]]'' (1988)\n* ''[[Kickin' (Rick James album)|Kickin']]'' (1989)\n* ''[[Urban Rapsody]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Deeper Still (album)|Deeper Still]]'' (2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Benjaminson|first=Peter|year=2017|title=Super Freak: The Life of Rick James|publisher=Chicago Review Press, Inc.|isbn=9781613749579}}\n* {{cite book|last=Denisof|first=R. Serge|year=1988|title=Inside MTV|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-0-88738-864-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Durchholz|first=Daniel|year=2010|title=Neil Young: Long May You Run: The Illustrated History, Updated Edition|publisher=Voyageur Press|isbn=9781610604536}}\n* {{cite book|last=James|first=Rick|year=2014|title=Glow: The Autobiography of Rick James|publisher=Atria Books|isbn=978-1-4767-6416-0|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikipedia books|Rick James}}\n* {{Official website|www.rickjames.com|Rick James}} \u2013 official site\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0416872|name=Rick James}}\n* {{Find a Grave|9276693}}\n* [http://www.thrasherswheat.org/friends/rick-james.htm Rick James, The Mynah Birds and Neil Young]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130724021404/http://longform.org/stories/rise-and-fall-of-a-super-freak Rise & Fall of a Super Freak]\n\n{{Rick James}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:James, Rick}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American guitarists]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:African-American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American expatriate musicians in Canada]]\n[[Category:American kidnappers]]\n[[Category:American funk bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American funk guitarists]]\n[[Category:American funk keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American funk singers]]\n[[Category:American male bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues guitarists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American rhythm and blues singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American soul guitarists]]\n[[Category:American soul keyboardists]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Cemetery, Buffalo]]\n[[Category:Cocaine-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Drug-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Motown artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Buffalo, New York]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Stroke survivors]]\n[[Category:United States Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:A&M Records artists]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records artists]]\n[[Category:African-American rock singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American keyboardists]]\n", "name_user": "Kaldari", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eKidnapping and assault convictions:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_James"}
{"title_page": "Blake Bortles", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name=Blake Bortles\n| image=20140914 Blake Bortles.jpg\n| image_size=\n| alt=\n| caption=Bortles with the Jaguars in 2014\n| current_team=Free Agent\n| number= \n| position=[[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1992|04|28}}\n| birth_place=[[Altamonte Springs, Florida]]\n| height_ft=6\n| height_in=5\n| weight_lbs=236\n| high_school=[[Oviedo High School|Oviedo]] ([[Oviedo, Florida]])\n| college=[[UCF Knights football|UCF]]\n| draftyear=2014\n| draftround=1\n| draftpick=3\n| pastteams=\n* [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] ({{NFL Year|2014}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Los Angeles Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2019}})\n| status=\n| highlights=\n* [[AFC_South|AFC South]] Champion ([[2017_Jacksonville_Jaguars_season|2017]])\n* [[American Athletic Conference football individual awards#Offensive Player of the Year|AAC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2013)\n* First-team All-[[American Athletic Conference|AAC]] (2013)\n* Second-team All-[[Conference USA]] (2012)\n| statseason=2019\n| statweek=\n| statlabel1=Completion %\n| statvalue1=59.3\n| statlabel2=[[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue2=103\u201375\n| statlabel3=Passing yards\n| statvalue3=17,649\n| statlabel4=[[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4=80.6\n| nflnew=blakebortles/2543477\n| pfr=BortBl00\n}}\n\n'''Robby Blake Bortles'''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://issuu.com/thelionstale/docs/edition7final/12 |title=The Lion's Tale \u2013 Volume 50, Issue 7 |access-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thespecktator.com/2015/09/01/blake-bortles-sure-taint-trying-impress-anyone/ |title=Blake Bortles sure 'taint' trying to impress anyone |last=Says |first=Shae |date=September 1, 2015 |website=Specktator |access-date=August 27, 2016}}</ref> (born April 28, 1992) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who is a [[free agent]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[UCF Knights football|University of Central Florida]] (UCF) and was drafted by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]] third overall in the [[2014 NFL Draft]].\n\nBortles' tenure in Jacksonville featured ups and downs, including setting team records for passing yards and touchdowns in a single season in 2015, and also leading the Jaguars to their first [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs|AFC Conference Championship game]] appearance since 1999, where they lost to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. However, Bortles also proved to be turnover-prone, leading the league in interceptions thrown (18) in 2015 and to a league-high 75 between 2014 and 2018. He was released by the Jaguars just one year into a $54 million contract extension, and signed with the [[Los Angeles Rams]] as a backup to [[Jared Goff]] in the offseason.\n\n==Early years==\nBortles attended [[Oviedo High School]] in [[Oviedo, Florida]], where he excelled in [[high school football|football]] and [[baseball]] for the Lions athletic teams.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.firstcoastnews.com/article/sports/nfl/jacksonville-jaguars/blake-bortles-high-school-coach-tells-all-about-the-quarterback/77-509313653 |title=Blake Bortles' high school coach tells all about the quarterback |work=WTLV |access-date=March 13, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> As a senior, he completed 151 of 233 passes for 2,211 yards with 27 [[touchdown]]s and seven [[interception]]s. He finished his high school career with a [[Seminole County, Florida|Seminole County]] record 5,576 career passing yards and 53 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://today.ucf.edu/qb-blake-bortles-helps-when-asked/ |title=QB Blake Bortles Helps When Asked |website=UCF News \u2013 University of Central Florida Articles \u2013 Orlando, FL News |language=en-US |access-date=November 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\nLabeled a three-star recruit by ''[[Rivals.com]]'', Bortles was listed as the No. 44 pro-style quarterback in his class.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-2388 |title=Rivals.com pro-style quarterbacks 2010 |website=[[Rivals.com]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Bortles chose UCF over offers from [[Colorado State Rams football|Colorado State]], [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]], [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]], and [[Western Kentucky Hilltoppers football|Western Kentucky]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.seminolechronicle.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2014/05/08/536b812d729ce |title=The Bortles File: Covering Blake Bortles through the years |last=Ryzewski |first=Steven |date=May 8, 2014 |work=[[Seminole Chronicle]] |access-date=May 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140510182246/http://www.seminolechronicle.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2014/05/08/536b812d729ce |archive-date=May 10, 2014}}\"After turning down offers from Purdue, Colorado State and Tulane, Oviedo quarterback Blake Bortles committed to UCF on Saturday.\"</ref>\n\n==College career==\nBortles accepted the offer from UCF, which was the first college to offer him a scholarship and was located near his home. He was [[redshirted]] as a true freshman in 2010. As a redshirt freshman in 2011, he played in 10 games, completing 75 of 110 passes for 958 yards with six [[touchdown]]s and three [[interception]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2011/ |title=Blake Bortles 2011 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> As a sophomore in 2012, he started all 14 games at quarterback. He completed 251 of 399 passes for 3,059 yards with 25 touchdowns and seven interceptions. He also rushed for 285 yards and scored eight touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Blake Bortles 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2013-08-27/sports/os-ucf-akron-football-0828-20130827_1_blake-bortles-jeff-godfrey-ucf-coach-george-o-leary |title=New year brings new expectations for UCF quarterback Blake Bortles |last=Tenorio |first=Paul |date=August 27, 2013 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\nHe was the MVP of the [[2012 Beef 'O' Brady's Bowl]] after completing 22 of 32 passes for 271 yards with three touchdowns and 79 rushing yards against the [[2012 Ball State Cardinals football team|Ball State Cardinals]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2012-12-21/sports/os-live-updates-ucf-ball-state-beef-bowl_1_latavius-murray-ucf-coach-george-o-leary-ucf-quarterback |title=UCF's Blake Bortles leads Knights to 38\u201317 win over Ball State in bowl |last=Tenorio |first=Paul |date=December 21, 2012 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bortles led the Knights to the inaugural championship of the [[American Athletic Conference]], earning the league's [[Automatic Qualifying conference|automatic berth]] to a [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] [[Bowl game|bowl]], the [[2014 Fiesta Bowl (January)|Tostitos Fiesta Bowl]]. Passing for 301 yards and rushing for 93 yards and four touchdowns, Bortles led UCF to an upset of fifth-ranked [[2013 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]], 52\u201342. Bortles was named the Offensive MVP of the game, which was UCF's first major bowl win in school history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/bowls/2014/01/02/central-florida-ucf-knights-baylor-bears-fiesta-bowl-blake-bortles/4284975/ |title=No. 15 UCF stuns No. 5 Baylor in Fiesta Bowl |last=Gillespie |first=Ryan |date=January 2, 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> In his final collegiate season, he was 259-of-382 for 3,581 yards, 25 touchdowns, and nine interceptions. In addition, he added 87 rushes for 272 yards and six rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/blake-bortles-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Blake Bortles 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Collegiate statistics===\nAs a starter from the 2012 and 2013 seasons, Bortles had a 22\u20135 ({{Winning percentage|22|5}}) record for the Knights. {{As of|2016}}, his career passer rating of 153.9 is the highest for any UCF quarterback with at least 500 pass attempts, and he was fourth in career completions, yards, and touchdowns behind [[Daunte Culpepper]], Ryan Schneider, and Darin Hinshaw.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://issuu.com/ucf_athletics/docs/2016_ucf_football_media_guide |title=2016 UCF Football Yearbook |date=2016 |website=issuu |pages=122\u2013125 |language=en |access-date=September 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/central-florida/passing.html |title=UCF Knights Passing |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#ba9b37; color:#000000;\" | Blake Bortles\n! colspan=9 | Passing\n! colspan=3 | Rushing\n|-\n! Year!! Team !! {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! {{tooltip|GS|Games started}} !! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! [[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]] || [[2011 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 10 || 0 || 75 || 110 || 67.8 || 958 || 6 || 3 || 153.9 || 21 || 4 || 1\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] || [[2012 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 14 || 14 || 251 || 399 || 62.9 || 3,059 || 25 || 7 || 144.5 || 87 || 285 || 8\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] || [[2013 UCF Knights football team|UCF]]\n| 13 || 13 || 259 || 382 || 67.8 || 3,581 || 25 || 9 || 163.4 || 87 || 272 || 6\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=2|Total<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/stats/_/id/505719/blake-bortles |title=Blake Bortles Stats \u2013 UCF Knights |website=ESPN.com |publisher=The Walt Disney Company |access-date=January 5, 2013}}</ref> || 37 || 27 || 585 || 891 || 66.2 || 7,598 || 56 || 19 || 153.9 || 195 || 561 || 15\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nOn January 5, 2014, Bortles announced that he would forgo his senior season and enter the [[2014 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000309706/article/report-ucf-qb-blake-bortles-to-declare-for-2014-nfl-draft |title=Report: UCF QB Blake Bortles to declare for 2014 NFL Draft |last=Greenspan |first=Dan |date=January 5, 2014 |work=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1908220-blake-bortles-reportedly-to-announce-he-will-enter-2014-nfl-draft |title=Blake Bortles Will Declare for 2014 NFL Draft |last=Clarke |first=Patrick |date=January 5, 2014 |work=[[Bleacher Report]] |access-date=May 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 5\n|       weight = 232\n|         dash = 4.93\n|    ten split = 1.75\n| twenty split = 2.86\n|      shuttle = 4.21\n|   cone drill = 7.08\n|     vertical = {{fraction|32|1|2}}\n|     broad ft = 9\n|     broad in = 5\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = 28<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/rating-the-nfl-draft-prospects-quarterbacks-b99258613z1-257586291.html |title=Rating the NFL draft prospects: Quarterbacks |last=McGinn |first=Bob |date=May 1, 2014 |website=JSOnline.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170816183502/http://archive.jsonline.com/sports/packers/rating-the-nfl-draft-prospects-quarterbacks-b99258613z1-257586291.html |archive-date=August 16, 2017 |access-date=June 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|     arm span = {{fraction|32|7|8}}\n|    hand span = {{fraction|9|3|8}}\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/blake-bortles?id=2543477 |title=Blake Bortles |website=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Jacksonville Jaguars===\n\nOn May 8, 2014, at the [[2014 NFL Draft]], Bortles was chosen in the first round with the third overall pick by the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]. Bortles was the first of an eventual 14 quarterbacks to be drafted.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000348037/article/jacksonville-jaguars-take-blake-bortles-with-no-3-pick |title=Jacksonville Jaguars take Blake Bortles with No. 3 pick |last=Rosenthal |first=Gregg |date=May 8, 2014 |work=nfl.com |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2014/5/8/5577756/nfl-draft-results-2014-blake-bortles-jaguars |title=NFL Draft results 2014: Blake Bortles goes No. 3 to Jaguars |last=Bien |first=Louis |date=May 8, 2014 |work=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season: Rookie year====\n[[File:Blake Bortles vs. Ravens 2014.jpg|thumb|200px|Bortles against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] in 2014]]\n{{see also|2014 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nOn June 18, 2014, Bortles signed his rookie contract worth $20.6&nbsp;million guaranteed for four years with the team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000359677/article/blake-bortles-signs-with-jacksonville-jaguars? |title=Blake Bortles, Jacksonville Jaguars strike contract |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[National Football League]] |access-date=June 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 3, Bortles made his NFL debut when he came in relief of [[Chad Henne]] in the second half of a 44\u201317 blowout loss to the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/jacksonville-jaguars-finally-turn-the-ball-over-to-blake-bortles-185111083.html |title=Jacksonville Jaguars finally turn the ball over to Blake Bortles |last=Edholm |first=Eric |date=September 21, 2014 |publisher=Yahoo Sports |access-date=September 21, 2014}}</ref> He went on to complete 14-of-24 passes for 223 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409210jax.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 2, 2017}}</ref> Following the game, head coach [[Gus Bradley]] named Bortles the starter going forward.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.firstcoastnews.com/article/sports/nfl/jacksonville-jaguars/bortles-named-future-starter-after-jags-44-17-loss-to-colts/77-270541100 |title=Bortles named future starter after Jags 44\u201317 loss to Colts |last=Gibson |first=Travis |website=WTLV |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In the next game, Bortles made his first NFL start against the [[2014 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]]. He ended the game 29-of-37 for 253 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in a 33\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409280sdg.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at San Diego Chargers \u2013 September 28th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> His 78.4 percent completion percentage set a record for a rookie quarterback's first start.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mmqb.si.com/2014/09/29/nfl-mvp-week-4-monday-morning-qb/7/ |title=DeMarco Murray, Philip Rivers lead NFL MVP race; Steve Smith Sr., more |last=King |first=Peter |website=SI.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141001233655/http://mmqb.si.com/2014/09/29/nfl-mvp-week-4-monday-morning-qb/7/ |archive-date=October 1, 2014}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2014 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], he produced 336 yards on 32-of-46 passes (three franchise rookie records), but the Jaguars lost 14\u201316 due to a blocked field goal.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410120oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 October 12th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During Week 13 against the [[2014 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Bortles threw for 194 yards, with one touchdown and no interceptions and 68 rushing yards in the Jaguars' largest comeback win in franchise history. They narrowly won 25\u201324 after trailing by 21 points.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411300jax.htm |title=New York Giants at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 November 30th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Three weeks later, he led the Jaguars to a ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' 21-13 victory over the Titans. He completed 13 of 26 passes for a touchdown and no interceptions along with 50 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412180jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 18th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBortles established himself as a [[dual-threat quarterback]] in his rookie season by rushing for 20 or more yards seven times in 2014, second only to [[Russell Wilson]] of the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2015082852/2015/PRE3/lions@jaguars#menu=drivechart%7CcontentId:0ap3000000517379&tab=videos |title=Watch Detroit Lions vs. Jacksonville Jaguars [08/28/2015] - NFL.com |website=www.nfl.com}}</ref> However, he also led the NFL and set franchise records in taking 55 sacks for 345 yards lost, and compiled a 3\u201310 record as a starter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00.htm |title=Blake Bortles Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=September 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2014.htm |title=2014 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n{{see also|2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nBortles, after having a strong preseason in his second year, started the 2015 season slow with a touchdown and two interceptions in the season-opening 20\u20139 loss to the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130jax.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref> In the next game, he led the Jaguars on a comeback drive against the [[2015 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] to seal their first victory of the season. Bortles threw for 273 yards and two touchdowns with no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200jax.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During Week 5 against the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Bortles threw for a then-career-high four touchdowns for 303 yards along with 21 rushing yards. However, this was not enough as the Jaguars lost 38\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510110tam.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 October 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref> During Week 13, he broke the Jaguars single game record with five touchdown passes in a 42\u201339 road loss to the [[2015 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512060oti.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Tennessee Titans \u2013 December 6th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Jaguars finished with a 5\u201311 record in 2015, and Bortles again led the league in sacks taken (51) and interceptions thrown (18).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2015.htm |title=2015 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> However, the season was also a success for the second-year quarterback in many ways. Bortles set the Jaguars single-season franchise records for passing touchdowns (35), passing yards, (4,428), pass completions (355), and pass attempts (606).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/single-season-passing.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars Single-Season Passing Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00/gamelog/2015 |title=Blake Bortles 2015 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> His 90-yard touchdown throw to [[Allen Robinson]] in Week 16 was the longest in the NFL that year. His passer rating was above 80 in eleven games, and he threw a touchdown pass in the Jaguars' first 15 games of 2015, a franchise record. After throwing no touchdowns in the regular season finale, he shared second place with [[Eli Manning]], [[Cam Newton]], and [[Carson Palmer]], behind only [[Tom Brady]]'s 36. He was also seventh in the NFL in passing yards with 4,428, behind [[Drew Brees]], [[Philip Rivers]], Brady, Palmer, [[Matt Ryan (American football)|Matt Ryan]], and Manning. He was ranked 56th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000666119/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-56-Blake-Bortles |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 56 Blake Bortles |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{see also|2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\n\nBortles compiled a disappointing 3\u201313 record for the 2016 Jaguars, amid considerable turnover in the organization.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2016.htm |title=2016 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> During a nine-game losing streak, offensive coordinator [[Greg Olson (American football)|Greg Olson]] was replaced by [[Nathaniel Hackett]] in Week 8, and head coach [[Gus Bradley]] by [[Doug Marrone]] in Week 16. The following week, Bortles caught his first career reception from wide receiver [[Marqise Lee]] on a 20-yard trick play that netted a touchdown and led to a [[Christmas Eve]] 38-17 victory over the [[2016 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201612240jax.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 1, 2017}}</ref> It was his only game with a [[passer rating]] of over 100 in 2016 (compared to five in 2015).\n\nBortles finished the 2016 season with 3,905 yards passing and a 58.9 completion percentage, 23 touchdown passes, 16 interceptions (4th in the NFL), but just 34 sacks, and five 300+ yard games (7th in the NFL).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/passing.htm |title=2016 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00/gamelog/2016 |title=Blake Bortles 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Following the season, he stated that he had suffered from a Grade 1 right AC joint sprain in Week 8, and suffered from wrist tendinitis in the latter part of the season, which could explain his regression.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/jaguars-blake-bortles-played-through-shoulder-wrist-concerns-in-2016/ |title=Jaguars' Blake Bortles: Played through shoulder, wrist concerns in 2016 |date=January 2, 2017 |website=CBSSports.com |access-date=December 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{see also|2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season}}\nOn May 1, 2017, the Jaguars picked up the fifth-year option on Bortles's contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000805448/article/jaguars-pick-up-blake-bortles-fifthyear-option |title=Jaguars pick up Blake Bortles' fifth-year option |last=Orr |first=Conor |date=May 1, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 26, he was named the starting quarterback to begin the regular season after a competition with [[Chad Henne]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000834769/article/blake-bortles-named-jaguars-starting-qb-for-week-1 |title=Blake Bortles named Jaguars' starting QB for Week 1 |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=August 26, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThrough the first 11 games of the season, Bortles was relatively inconsistent. He had an excellent Week 3 with four passing touchdowns and no interceptions for a 128.2 rating in a 44-7 victory over the [[2017 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] in London.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709240jax.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 September 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> He broke 300 yards passing just once in Week 7 with 330 passing yards, one passing touchdown and no interceptions for a 124.7 rating against the [[2017 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710220clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 October 22nd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Excluding these games, Bortles averaged 185.6 yards per game, no games of either 300+ yards or 100+ rating, and had seven touchdowns and eight interceptions in those nine games. Through 12 weeks, out of the 20 eleven-game starters, Bortles was 17th in yardage and touchdowns, and 18th in rating. However, he had a 100+ rating in the next three consecutive games, compiling 8 touchdowns and 0 interceptions, and 300+ yards in three of the next four games.\n\nDuring Week 15 against the [[2017 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Bortles finished with 326 passing yards and three passing touchdowns as the Jaguars won, 45\u20137, helping the team clinch their first playoff berth in 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712170jax.htm |title=Houston Texans at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 December 17th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> In the next game against the [[2017 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Bortles finished with a season-best 382 passing yards, two passing touchdowns, and three interceptions as the Jaguars lost on the road by a score of 44\u201333.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712240sfo.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at San Francisco 49ers \u2013 December 24th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> Despite the loss, the Jaguars clinched the AFC South due to the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Titans]] losing to the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/week_16.htm |title=2017 NFL Week 16 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> Bortles finished the regular season with 3,687 passing yards, 21 touchdowns to 13 interceptions, and an 84.7 quarterback rating (21st of 35 players with at least 200 attempts).<ref>{{cite web |title=2017 NFL Passing Statistics |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/x17NS}}</ref>\n\nAfter finishing 10\u20136, the Jaguars made the playoffs as the #3-seed in the 2017 AFC Playoffs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2017/12/31/jags-say-theyre-ready-for-playoffs-after-losing-2-straight/109069718/ |title=Jags say they're ready for playoffs after losing 2 straight |work=USA TODAY |access-date=January 7, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_10,_Buffalo_Bills_3|Wild Card Round]], the Jaguars defeated the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] by a score of 10\u20133 in Bortles's first playoff game. He completed 12 of 23 passes for 87 yards and a touchdown.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/16724/year/2017 |title=Blake Bortles |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He also had a game-high 88 yards rushing on 10 carries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/gamelog/_/id/12514/lesean-mccoy |title=LeSean McCoy |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He joined [[Michael Vick]] (2004) as the only quarterbacks with more rushing than passing yards in a postseason game since the 1970 merger,<ref>[https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1970&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=P&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=pass_att&c1comp=gt&c1val=10&c2stat=rush_yds&c2comp=gt&c2val=30&c3stat=pass_yds&c3comp=lt&c3val=181&c5val=3&c6stat=rush_yds&order_by=rush_yds Players with 10+ pass attempts, <181 passing yards, and >40 rushing yards], on PFR. 181 is the record for most rushing yards by a quarterback in a post-season game.</ref> and the 75 net passing yards was the lowest by a winning postseason quarterback since [[Joe Flacco]] in the 2009 postseason.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/rdOEJ |title=Teams winning in the postseason with 75 or fewer passing yards |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Due to his poor passing performance against the Bills, Bortles received heavy criticism from analysts and even other players in the league. When confronted about these criticisms, Bortles stated that he \"couldn't care less\" and even said, \"There's people who think [[LeBron James]] sucks, so if that happens, I\u2019m sure there will always be people who always think I suck.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/jaguars/2018/01/14/blake-bortles-shrugs-off-critics-couldnt-care-less/1033230001/ |title=Jaguars QB Blake Bortles shrugs off critics: 'I couldn't care less' |last=Reyes |first=Lorenzo |work=USA TODAY |access-date=January 15, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/01/blake-bortles-lebron-james-haters-sucks-always-fans-jaguars-nfl |title=Blake Bortles draws strength from LeBron James to dismiss his haters |last=Tsuji |first=Alysha |date=January 10, 2018 |work=For The Win |access-date=January 15, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> However, Bortles bounced back in the [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC:_Jacksonville_Jaguars_45,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_42|Divisional Round]], leading the Jaguars to beat the heavily favored [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] on the road by a score of 45\u201342. Bortles completed 14 of 26 passes for 214 yards and a touchdown to stifle a Steelers comeback.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bigcatcountry.com/2018/1/15/16892702/blake-bortles-did-what-he-needed-to-win-again |title=Blake Bortles did what he needed to win, again |last=Crow |first=Alfie |work=Big Cat Country |access-date=January 15, 2018}}</ref> This would be Jacksonville's first [[2017\u201318_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship_Game:_New_England_Patriots_24,_Jacksonville_Jaguars_20|AFC Championship]] game since 1999, but they lost to the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] on the road by a score of 24\u201320 after spoiling a 20\u201310 lead in the fourth quarter. Bortles finished the game completing 23 of 36 passes for 293 yards and a touchdown. He finished the playoffs completing 57.6% of his passes for 594 yards, three touchdowns, and no interceptions. He also rushed for 121 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/player/blakebortles/2543477/gamelogs |title=Blake Bortles: Game Logs at NFL.com |website=www.nfl.com |language=en |access-date=January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn February 24, 2018, Bortles signed a three-year, $54&nbsp;million contract to stay with the Jaguars through the 2020 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000917453/article/jaguars-sign-blake-bortles-to-3year-54m-contract |title=Jaguars sign Blake Bortles to 3-year, $54M contract |last=Shook |first=Nick |date=February 24, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBortles and the Jaguars had a 3\u20131 start to the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/2018.htm |title=2018 Jacksonville Jaguars Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Between sub-200 yard games in Week 1 and Week 3, Bortles faced the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] in 97-degree heat and finished with 377 passing yards, four touchdowns, and an interception in the 31\u201320 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2018/09/16/blake-bortles-jaguars-patriots-31-20 |title=Blake Bortles throws 4 TDs, Jaguars beat Patriots 31\u201320 in rematch |last=Long |first=Mark |date=September 16, 2018 |work=Boston.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In Week 4, he passed for 388 yards in a 31\u201312 win over the [[2018 New York Jets season|Jets]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/30/bortles-tosses-2-td-passes-jags-handle-darnold-jets-31-12/37999871/ |title=Bortles tosses 2 TD passes, Jags handle Darnold, Jets 31\u201312 |work=USA TODAY |access-date=October 29, 2018 |agency=Associated Press |language=en}}</ref> In the next game, he recorded a career-high 430 passing yards and a touchdown against the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. However, he also threw four interceptions and took five sacks in the 30\u201314 road loss.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/jacksonville-jaguars-kansas-city-chiefs-score-recap-100718 |title=Kansas City Chiefs 30, Jacksonville Jaguars 14 |date=October 7, 2018 |work=FOX Sports |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> The following week against the [[2018 Dallas Cowboys|Dallas Cowboys]], Bortles threw for 149 yards, a touchdown, and an interception to [[Jeff Heath (American football)|Jeff Heath]] in triple coverage in a 40\u20137 road loss.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/jaguars-blake-bortles-struggles-in-loss-to-cowboys/ |title=Jaguars' Blake Bortles: Struggles in loss to Cowboys |date=October 14, 2018 |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> During  Week 7 against the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], he lost a fumble on the opening possessions of each half. Bortles was benched for [[Cody Kessler]] after he lost the second fumble, finishing the day with a career-low 61 yards on 12 attempts.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/blake-bortles-benched-for-cody-kessler-the-former-browns-qb-who-is-0-8-as-an-nfl-starter/ |title=Blake Bortles benched for Cody Kessler, the former Browns QB who is 0\u20138 as an NFL starter |last=Wilson |first=Ryan |work=CBSSports.com |access-date=October 29, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> At the time, the Jaguars had the league's second-best defense but had lost three games in a row; Bortles was tied for second-worst in the league with four sub-200 yard passing games, third-worst with eight interceptions, and seventh-worst with five fumbles. Nevertheless, head coach [[Doug Marrone]] elected to leave Bortles as the starter for the Week 8 matchup in London against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. He fumbled the opening snap, but played through a shoulder injury to finish with 286 yards and a touchdown. He led the Jaguars on three straight scoring drives late in the game to draw within six points before completing just two of his last nine passes in the 18\u201424 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/10/22/jaguars-starting-quarterback-open-doug-marrone-blake-bortles-cody-kessler |title=Marrone says Bortles will start for Jags vs. Eagles |last=Rollins |first=Khadrice |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201810280jax.htm |title=Philadelphia Eagles at Jacksonville Jaguars \u2013 October 28th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 10, 2018}}</ref> After a Week 9 bye, the Jaguars went on the road to face the [[2018 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. Bortles finished the game with 320 yards and two touchdowns. He completed 10 of 11 passes for two scoring drives to open the second half, and a drive to the 23 yard line in the waning moments of the 4th quarter before a [[Rashad Greene]] fumble allowed the Colts to kneel out the clock and preserve a 29-26 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201811110clt.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 11th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> In the next game, Bortles completed 10 of 18 passes for a career-fourth-worst 104 yards in a 20-16 loss to the [[2018 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2018111810/2018/REG11/Steelers@Jaguars?icampaign=scoreStrip-globalNav-2018111810 |title=Steelers vs Jaguars |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=November 19, 2018}}</ref>  The following week, he completed 12 of 23 passes for 127 yards and a touchdown with two interceptions in a 21\u201324 road loss to the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.jaguars.com/news/game-report-bills-24-jaguars-21?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Game report: Bills 24, Jaguars 21 |last=Oehser |first=John |website=www.jaguars.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> The next day, Jaguars head coach Doug Marrone announced that Bortles would be benched in favor of Cody Kessler for the Week 13 matchup against the Colts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000992852/article/jaguars-to-start-cody-kessler-for-week-13-vs-colts |title=Jaguars bench Blake Bortles, will start Cody Kessler |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=November 26, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> He was then 30th of 34 qualified quarterbacks in completion percentage, quarterback rating, and yards-per-attempt, and second-worst only to [[Oakland Raiders|Oakland]]'s [[Derek Carr]] with eight losses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/C3IIm |title=NFL passing statistics, Weeks 1\u201312 of the 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> In Week 16 against the [[2018 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Bortles entered the game in relief of a struggling Kessler in the late second quarter, was promptly sacked on third down, benched, then reentered the game in the late third quarter where he completed five of six passes for 39 yards and rushed four times for 26 yards to help lead the Jaguars to a 17\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812230mia.htm |title=Jacksonville Jaguars at Miami Dolphins \u2013 December 23rd, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> Bortles started the season finale against the Texans,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001004484/article/blake-bortles-named-starter-for-jaguars-season-finale |title=Blake Bortles named starter for Jaguars' season finale |last=Teope |first=Herbie |date=December 26, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref> but was ineffective with just 107 yards and an interception on 28 attempts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sltrib.com/sports/2018/12/31/ravens-eagles-colts/ |title=Ravens, Eagles, Colts squeeze into NFL playoffs; Steelers, Vikings, Titans out |website=The Salt Lake Tribune |language=en-US |access-date=January 22, 2019 |last3=2018 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On the season, in Bortles' 13 appearances for the Jaguars, he compiled a 4\u20139 record,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BortBl00.htm |title=Blake Bortles 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> and was 22nd of 25 players with at least 13 appearances in completion percentage (60.3%), yards (2,718), yards per game (209.1), touchdowns (13), and 23rd in passer rating (79.8); his 11 interceptions ranked 15th. His 357 rushing yards was sixth among quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/8Y476 |title=2018 Passing Statistics, 13+ Games |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBortles was released by the Jaguars on March 13, 2019, after the team signed quarterback [[Nick Foles]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001022563/article/jaguars-release-qb-blake-bortles-after-signing-foles |title=Jaguars release QB Blake Bortles after signing Foles |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=March 13, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref> Over his five years with the Jaguars, Bortles led the league in interceptions (75 in 75 games, a league-leading 13 of which were returned for touchdowns) and second among quarterbacks in fumbles (46) to [[Russell Wilson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/46QbD |title=Turnovers by Quarterbacks, 2014-18 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Rams===\nOn March 18, 2019, Bortles signed a one-year contract with the [[Los Angeles Rams]] to be [[Jared Goff]]'s backup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.therams.com/news/qb-blake-bortles-agree-to-terms-on-one-year-contract |title=Rams, QB Blake Bortles agree to terms on one-year contract |last=Simmons |first=Myles |date=March 18, 2019 |website=TheRams.com |access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\nBortles played three snaps of a Week 7 blowout of the [[2019 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] with a 20 point lead late in the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thefalcoholic.com/2019/10/20/20923495/falcons-10-rams-37-atlanta-blown-out-is-dan-quinn-going-to-be-fired-soon |title=Falcons 10, Rams 37: Atlanta gets demolished and Dan Quinn may get fired |last=Walker |first=David J. |date=October 20, 2019 |website=[[SB Nation|The Falcoholic]] |access-date=October 21, 2019}}</ref> He failed to pick up a first down on 3rd and 2 in his only play in a Week 10 loss to the [[2019 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], and had his first completion of the season during seven plays with a 27 point lead in the fourth quarter of a Week 13 34-7 victory over the [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Rams at Arizona Cardinals - December 1st, 2019 |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201912010crd.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n====Regular season====\n{|class= \"wikitable sortable\" float=\"left\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:center; width:45%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|GP !! rowspan=\"2\"|GS !! colspan=\"8\" |Passing  !! colspan=\"4\" |Rushing !! colspan=\"2\" |Sacked !! colspan=\"2\" |Fumbles\n|-\n! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Y/A !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Sack !! Yds !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] || [[2014 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| 14 || 13 || 280 || 475 || 58.9 || 2,908 || 6.1 || 11 || 17 || 69.5 || 56 || '''419''' || '''7.5''' || 0 || '''55''' || '''345''' || 7 || 3\n|- \n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] || [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 355 || 606 || 58.6 || '''4,428''' || '''7.3''' || '''35''' || '''18''' || '''88.2''' || 52 || 310 || 6.0 || 2 || 51 || 320 || '''14''' || '''5'''\n|- \n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || '''368''' || '''625''' || 58.9 || 3,905 || 6.2 || 23 || 16 || 78.8 || '''58''' || 359 || 6.2 || '''3''' || 34 || 197 || 8 || 0\n|- \n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] || [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 315 || 523 || 60.2 || 3,687 || 7.0 || 21 || 13 || 84.7 || 57 || 322 || 5.6 || 2 || 24 || 123 || 9 || 3\n|- \n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|JAX]]\n| 13 || 12 || 243 || 403 || '''60.3''' || 2,718  || 6.7 || 13 || 11 || 79.8 || '''58''